(1,'Ancient Civilizations',1,5,
'What was the ancient Egyptians'' own name for their homeland?',
'["Kemet — The Black Land","Aegyptos — Land of the Gods","Pharaon — Kingdom of the Sun","Deshret — The Red Desert"]',
0,'historical',
'The ancient Egyptians called their land Kemet — The Black Land — referring to the fertile dark silt deposited by the Nile floods. The name Egypt comes from the Greek Aegyptos, itself from the Egyptian Hwt-Ka-Ptah (Temple of the Soul of Ptah). Kemet was contrasted with Deshret — the barren Red Land of the desert — a duality that permeated all Egyptian cosmology.',
'The black fertile land and red desert were not just geography — they were a cosmic map. Osiris ruled Kemet, Set ruled Deshret. All Egyptian metaphysics emerged from this primal tension between life and death, order and chaos, nourishment and destruction.',
'ancient egypt nile kemet black land hieroglyphs',
ARRAY['egypt','names','history','kemet']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',1,5,
'Why is Göbekli Tepe in Turkey considered one of the most significant archaeological discoveries?',
'["It predates agriculture by 6000+ years, proving organised religion preceded farming","It is the largest known ancient city with over 100,000 inhabitants","It contains the oldest written language predating Sumerian by 3000 years","It proves ancient Egyptians had a global empire reaching Anatolia"]',
0,'empirical',
'Göbekli Tepe contains massive carved stone pillars assembled into ritual circles dating to 9500–8000 BCE — roughly 6000 years before Stonehenge and before the invention of agriculture. This overturned the long-held theory that organised religion and monument-building emerged only after settled farming.',
'Göbekli Tepe suggests that the human impulse toward the sacred — toward gathering, ceremony, and monumental construction — may have preceded and even motivated the agricultural revolution. Hunters and gatherers built temples before they built granaries.',
'Gobekli Tepe Turkey ancient stone circle neolithic',
ARRAY['turkey','neolithic','religion','archaeology','gobekli tepe']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',4,15,
'The Dogon people of Mali are remarkable in esoteric circles for their traditional knowledge about which star?',
'["Sirius B — an invisible companion star to Sirius A they described in detail before its telescopic confirmation","Orion''s Belt — which they claimed contained the throne of their creator god","Aldebaran — which they used to predict floods thousands of years before the Nile calendar","Polaris — which they tracked through a 26000-year precession cycle"]',
0,'speculative',
'The Dogon reportedly possessed detailed knowledge of Sirius B — a white dwarf companion star invisible to the naked eye — long before its photographic confirmation in 1970. They described its 50-year orbital period and extraordinary density. Whether this knowledge came from ancient contact, sophisticated observation, or was transmitted by anthropologist Marcel Griaule in the 1930s remains genuinely debated.',
'This case sits precisely at the boundary between empirical astronomy and esoteric transmission. Whatever its ultimate source, the Dogon material forces a genuine question: how much astronomical knowledge existed in pre-technological societies that we have simply never asked them about?',
'Dogon Mali Africa star astronomy Sirius',
ARRAY['dogon','sirius','africa','astronomy','esoteric']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',4,15,
'The Antikythera Mechanism recovered from an ancient Greek shipwreck is considered remarkable because it is:',
'["An analog computer with 30+ gears that tracked celestial cycles with extraordinary precision","The earliest known navigational compass, predating the Chinese version by 500 years","The first mechanical clock, capable of tracking time to the second","A surgical device demonstrating advanced ancient Greek medicine"]',
0,'empirical',
'Dating to approximately 100–150 BCE, the Antikythera Mechanism contains at least 30 interlocking bronze gears that predicted solar and lunar eclipses, tracked the five known planets, and calculated the Olympic Games cycle. Its technological sophistication was not matched again until 14th-century astronomical clocks in Europe.',
'The Mechanism forces a profound question: if this level of precision existed in 150 BCE, what other sophisticated technologies existed in the ancient world and simply did not survive? Its existence suggests ancient technological development was punctuated — with peaks of sophistication that were lost and had to be rediscovered centuries later.',
'Antikythera mechanism ancient greek bronze gears astronomy',
ARRAY['greece','technology','astronomy','antikythera','ancient machine']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',4,15,
'The Great Pyramid of Giza''s four narrow shafts appear to align with:',
'["Specific stars including Orion''s Belt and Sirius as they appeared around 2500 BCE","The four cardinal compass directions with perfect north alignment","Sunrise and sunset positions during the solstices","The positions of planets during a rare 2500-year conjunction"]',
0,'historical',
'Architectural researcher Robert Bauval identified that the Great Pyramid''s shafts appear to align with specific stars as positioned around 2500 BCE: the southern shafts point toward Orion''s Belt (Osiris) and Sirius (Isis), while northern shafts align with circumpolar stars including Alpha Draconis — then the pole star. The alignment of the three main Giza pyramids to Orion''s Belt is also frequently noted.',
'If intentional, the Great Pyramid functions simultaneously as a tomb, an astronomical instrument, and a mythological statement in stone — encoding the Egyptian understanding that death, stellar rebirth, and cosmic order are inseparable. The building is a cosmology made physical.',
'Great Pyramid Giza Egypt stars Orion astronomy alignments',
ARRAY['egypt','pyramids','astronomy','orion','alignments']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',12,50,
'Nabta Playa in the Egyptian Sahara contains what archaeoastronomical feature predating Stonehenge?',
'["Stone circles from 5000 BCE aligned with the summer solstice sunrise and the rising of Orion","The earliest agricultural settlement in the world, predating Sumerian farming by 3000 years","The oldest hieroglyphic inscriptions found outside the Nile Valley","A massive underground city that served as the blueprint for early Egyptian civilisation"]',
0,'historical',
'Nabta Playa contains stone circles and stellar alignments dating to approximately 5000 BCE — roughly 1000 years before Stonehenge. These structures appear aligned with the summer solstice sunrise and the rising of Orion. The site was used by prehistoric pastoralists who occupied the region during the African Humid Period when the Sahara supported grassland.',
'Nabta Playa suggests that the astronomical and ritual impulses that culminated in Egyptian civilisation had deep prehistoric roots among nomadic pastoralists of the Sahara. The astronomers of Nabta Playa may have been ancestors of those who built the pyramids — their cosmological traditions preserved over millennia.',
'Nabta Playa desert Egypt ancient stone circle astronomy',
ARRAY['egypt','sahara','archaeoastronomy','prehistoric','stone circles']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',12,50,
'The Mayan Dresden Codex, one of the oldest surviving Mayan books, primarily contains:',
'["Astronomical tables for Venus cycles, solar eclipses, and the 260-day sacred calendar","A complete history of Mayan kings from the founding of civilisation to the Spanish conquest","Agricultural planting guides tied to the solar year and rainfall predictions","Prophecies concerning the end of the current world age in what the West called 2012"]',
0,'historical',
'The Dresden Codex (dated 1200–1250 CE, though based on much older sources) contains sophisticated astronomical tables — most notably a Venus table tracking the 584-day synodic cycle of Venus with accuracy equivalent to modern astronomy, as well as eclipse tables, Mars tables, and calculations for the 260-day tzolkin sacred calendar. The Mayan astronomical precision documented in this text is remarkable.',
'The Venus table in the Dresden Codex tracks Venus''s cycle with an error of only 2 hours over 481 years. This level of astronomical precision, achieved through systematic naked-eye observation over centuries, speaks to a civilisation that considered the movements of the planets a matter of sacred importance — a living cosmos that required attentive reading.',
'Maya Dresden Codex ancient manuscript astronomy Venus',
ARRAY['maya','dresden codex','astronomy','venus','ancient books']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',12,50,
'The ancient Sumerian city of Eridu is significant because:',
'["It is considered the oldest city in the world (c. 5400 BCE) and the mythological birthplace of civilisation in Sumerian tradition","It contains the only known intact Sumerian library with over 30000 clay tablets","It was the first city to develop a writing system — all other scripts derived from Eridu''s original pictographs","It sits at the geographic centre of the ancient Near East and served as a religious capital for all Mesopotamian cultures"]',
0,'historical',
'Eridu (modern Tell Abu Shahrain in Iraq) dates to approximately 5400 BCE and is widely considered the world''s oldest city. In Sumerian mythology, Eridu was the first city lowered from heaven to earth, and was associated with Enki — the god of wisdom, fresh water, and civilisation. The site contains at least 18 successive temples built upon each other, suggesting continuous sacred use over millennia.',
'The Sumerian foundation myth places the origin of civilisation not in agricultural technology but in divine gift — the gods gave humanity the ''me'' (divine decrees or civilisational arts: writing, law, music, kingship) at Eridu. Whether understood literally or metaphorically, this origin narrative locates the birth of culture in a vertical transmission from a higher order, not a horizontal evolutionary process.',
'ancient Sumer Mesopotamia Eridu city ruins Iraq archaeology',
ARRAY['sumer','eridu','mesopotamia','oldest city','ancient civilisation']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',1,5,
'The ancient Egyptian concept of "Ma''at" refers to:',
'["Cosmic order, truth, justice, and harmony — the principle that governs both the universe and human society","The divine feminine creator goddess who separated earth from sky at the beginning of time","The afterlife realm where souls were judged before proceeding to paradise","The sacred knowledge held exclusively by pharaohs and high priests of Heliopolis"]',
0,'historical',
'Ma''at was both a goddess (depicted with an ostrich feather) and an abstract principle — the cosmic force of truth, order, balance, and justice that permeated all creation. Pharaohs were obligated to uphold Ma''at; the universe itself operated according to Ma''at. In the afterlife, the deceased''s heart was weighed against Ma''at''s feather — if balanced, the soul proceeded to paradise; if heavier with misdeeds, the heart was devoured by Ammit.',
'Ma''at represents one of the most sophisticated ancient conceptions of cosmic ethics — the idea that moral order and physical order are not separate domains but the same principle operating at different scales. When a human lies, steals, or acts unjustly, they are not merely violating a social contract but disrupting the fabric of cosmic reality. Ma''at connects individual ethics to universal physics in a way that Western thought largely separated after the Enlightenment.',
'ancient Egypt Ma''at goddess feather balance justice cosmic',
ARRAY['egypt','maat','cosmic order','ethics','afterlife']),

(1,'Ancient Civilizations',4,15,
'What makes the ancient Indian city of Dwarka (off the coast of Gujarat) archaeologically significant?',
'["Underwater ruins discovered at 40m depth match the ancient description of the sunken city of Lord Krishna in the Mahabharata","It is the oldest known continuously inhabited city in the world, with settlement dating to 10000 BCE","It contains the earliest evidence of iron smelting, predating the Near Eastern Iron Age by 2000 years","It is where the earliest proto-Sanskrit inscriptions were discovered, linking Indian and Sumerian writing systems"]',
0,'speculative',
'Marine archaeology surveys led by the National Institute of Ocean Technology (India) beginning in 2000 discovered submerged structures off Dwarka at depths of 30–40 metres, including a city grid with stone anchors, walls, and artifacts. The site has been tentatively dated to approximately 9000–7500 BCE, potentially corresponding to post-glacial sea level rise. Dwarka is described in the Mahabharata as the legendary city of Krishna that sank into the sea.',
'The Dwarka discovery sits in the fascinating territory where mythology and archaeology potentially intersect. If the submerged structures are confirmed as a human settlement from 9000+ BCE, it would suggest that sophisticated urban planning existed in India at a time when mainstream history assumes only hunter-gatherer societies. It also raises the question of how many other ancient coastal cities were swallowed by post-glacial sea level rise.',
'Dwarka India underwater ancient ruins ocean archaeology',
ARRAY['dwarka','india','underwater archaeology','ancient cities','krishna']),

