(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',1,5,
'According to the Kybalion, what is the First Hermetic Principle?',
'["Mentalism: The All is Mind; the Universe is Mental","Correspondence: As above, so below; as below, so above","Vibration: Nothing rests; everything moves; everything vibrates","Rhythm: Everything flows, out and in; everything has its tides"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Principle of Mentalism states that the entire Universe is mental — that The All (the Absolute, the Infinite Living Mind) creates all reality as a thought within infinite consciousness. This does not dismiss physical reality as illusion but declares its fundamental nature is consciousness, not matter. It is the master key from which all other Hermetic principles are derived.',
'The Principle of Mentalism finds remarkable resonance in quantum physics, where the observer effect suggests consciousness plays a role in collapsing possibility into observable reality. Whether metaphorical resonance or a deeper truth about the mental nature of the universe remains one of the most fascinating open questions at the intersection of ancient wisdom and modern science.',
'hermetic wisdom sacred geometry mind universe light',
ARRAY['hermeticism','kybalion','mentalism','principles','as above so below']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',1,5,
'"As above, so below" originates from which foundational Hermetic text?',
'["The Emerald Tablet attributed to Hermes Trismegistus","The Corpus Hermeticum — Dialogue I (Poemandres)","The Kybalion (1908) authored by The Three Initiates","Plato''s Timaeus describing the relationship of Forms to matter"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The phrase derives from the Emerald Tablet (Tabula Smaragdina) — one of the most influential documents in Western alchemy and esoteric philosophy. The oldest known Arabic version dates to the 6th–8th century CE. The full phrase reads: "That which is above is like that which is below, and that which is below is like that which is above, to accomplish the miracles of the one thing."',
'The Emerald Tablet distills the entire Hermetic worldview into a few sentences — macrocosm and microcosm mirror each other, the celestial and terrestrial reflect the same principles, and understanding one level of reality illuminates all others. This single principle has influenced Renaissance alchemy, Jungian psychology, and modern complexity theory.',
'Emerald Tablet alchemy Hermes ancient gold mystical',
ARRAY['hermeticism','emerald tablet','as above so below','alchemy','macrocosm']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',4,15,
'In Hermetic alchemy, the Philosopher''s Stone was primarily understood by serious alchemists as:',
'["Spiritual transformation — the transmutation of the base human soul into gold (enlightenment)","A literal physical substance capable of turning lead into gold for material wealth","A secret society membership code used by early Rosicrucians","An ancient meteorite containing unique catalytic properties"]',
0,'esoteric',
'While exoteric alchemy sought to literally transmute base metals into gold, esoteric alchemy used the same language metaphorically for spiritual transformation. The Philosopher''s Stone represented the perfected spiritual state — dissolution of the ego (nigredo/blackening), purification (albedo/whitening), and emergence of spiritual gold (rubedo/reddening). Many serious alchemists including Paracelsus understood alchemy primarily as a psychological and spiritual art.',
'Carl Jung devoted decades to alchemical texts, concluding that alchemists were unconsciously projecting their psychological processes onto matter. The stages of alchemical transformation (nigredo, albedo, citrinitas, rubedo) map almost perfectly onto Jung''s individuation process. The alchemists were doing genuine inner work while believing they were transforming metals — an extraordinary case of parallel discovery across two domains.',
'alchemy philosopher stone gold transformation medieval laboratory',
ARRAY['alchemy','philosopher stone','transformation','hermetic','jung']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',4,15,
'The Fibonacci sequence converges to which ratio that appears throughout nature and sacred geometry?',
'["The Golden Ratio (φ), approximately 1.618","Pi (π), approximately 3.14159","The square root of 2, approximately 1.414","Euler''s number (e), approximately 2.718"]',
0,'empirical',
'The Fibonacci sequence (1,1,2,3,5,8,13,21...) converges to the Golden Ratio (phi ≈ 1.618033...). This ratio appears in the spiral arrangement of sunflower seeds, pinecone scales, nautilus shells, hurricane patterns, galaxy spirals, and human body proportions. The ancient Greeks considered it the most aesthetically perfect proportion and embedded it in the Parthenon''s architecture.',
'The omnipresence of the Golden Ratio in natural growth patterns suggests it is not a human construct but a fundamental principle of how matter organises itself under the constraints of efficiency and space. When sacred geometry practitioners place the Golden Ratio at the centre of their cosmology, they are pointing at something genuinely remarkable about the mathematical nature of reality.',
'fibonacci golden ratio nautilus shell sacred geometry spiral nature',
ARRAY['fibonacci','golden ratio','sacred geometry','mathematics','nature']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',4,15,
'The Hermetic Principle of Polarity states:',
'["Everything has its pair of opposites; opposites are identical in nature, differing only in degree","Opposites are fundamentally different substances that exist in eternal conflict","Every action produces an equal and opposite reaction — the Hermetic anticipation of Newton''s third law","All creation oscillates between two poles: the material and the spiritual"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Principle of Polarity from the Kybalion states that all apparent opposites are the same thing differing only in degree: hot and cold are both "temperature," light and dark are both "illumination," love and hate are both "feeling." This has profound practical implications — you can transmute one pole into another by moving along the same continuum. Fear can be transformed into courage; hatred into love; because they are already on the same spectrum.',
'The Hermetic Principle of Polarity is both a cosmological statement and a practical psycho-spiritual tool. If all opposites exist on the same continuum, then no negative state is permanent or absolute — it is always possible to raise the vibration toward the positive pole. This is the Hermetic basis for what modern psychology calls "cognitive reframing" and what spiritual traditions call transformation.',
'hermetic polarity yin yang opposites balance sacred',
ARRAY['hermeticism','polarity','opposites','kybalion','transformation']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',12,50,
'What does the Corpus Hermeticum''s Poemandres reveal about the nature of the human mind and its relationship to the divine?',
'["Individual human minds are divine sparks of the All''s infinite mind that descended into matter and can return through gnosis","The human mind was created by the Demiurge as an imperfect copy of the divine mind and cannot return to the source","Mind is a universal substance distinct from both matter and spirit — the third element of the Hermetic trinity","Human minds are temporary configurations of the universal mental substance that dissolve back into it at death"]',
0,'esoteric',
'In the Poemandres, the divine Mind (Poemandres) reveals to Hermes that individual human minds are essentially of the same nature as the All — divine sparks that have descended into the material world through the seven planetary spheres, acquiring characteristics (ego, passions, desires) at each level. The path of return involves recognising one''s true divine nature through gnosis and gradually shedding the planetary acquisitions as one ascends back to the source.',
'The Hermetic vision of the human mind as a localised expression of the infinite divine Mind is one of the most radical affirmations of human dignity in any tradition. It does not say humans are fallen creatures in need of external salvation — it says they are divine beings who have temporarily forgotten their nature. The entire spiritual path, in this view, is not about becoming something new but remembering what one already and always is.',
'Corpus Hermeticum ancient manuscript Hermes divine wisdom',
ARRAY['corpus hermeticum','poemandres','hermes trismegistus','divine mind','gnosis']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',12,50,
'The seven Hermetic principles of the Kybalion correspond in remarkable ways to which modern scientific framework?',
'["Quantum field theory and systems theory — Mentalism (information primacy), Vibration (quantum fields), Correspondence (scale invariance), Polarity (quantum superposition)","Classical Newtonian mechanics — each principle maps to one of Newton''s laws of motion","Darwinian evolutionary theory — the principles describe stages in the evolution of consciousness","General relativity — the principles describe how spacetime curves in the presence of mental energy"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The correspondences are striking though not perfect: Mentalism parallels information-theoretic views of physics and quantum mechanics'' measurement problem (consciousness and observation playing fundamental roles). Vibration maps to the quantum field concept (all matter as vibrating energy). Correspondence mirrors scale invariance and fractal self-similarity across natural systems. Polarity echoes quantum superposition. Whether these are deep structural parallels or coincidental mappings remains philosophically rich territory.',
'The Kybalion was published in 1908 — the same year as Einstein''s first quantum paper. The parallel development of Hermetic philosophy and quantum physics in the early 20th century, without any documented mutual influence, is itself a kind of synchronicity. It suggests both may be reaching, through very different methods, toward the same underlying structure of reality.',
'hermetic principles sacred geometry quantum physics science',
ARRAY['kybalion','seven principles','quantum physics','hermetic','science']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',1,5,
'Mystery Schools of the ancient world (Eleusinian, Pythagorean, Orphic) shared what core practice?',
'["Initiatory experiences designed to produce direct experiential knowledge of death and rebirth before physical death","Public theatrical performances of mythological stories for mass spiritual education","Competitive examinations of philosophical knowledge to identify suitable philosopher-kings","Secret mathematical research programmes funded by city-states for astronomical purposes"]',
0,'historical',
'Mystery Schools provided initiatory experiences (often involving fasting, ritual, darkness, symbolic death, and rebirth) designed to give initiates direct experiential knowledge — gnosis — of what would otherwise remain merely theoretical. The Eleusinian Mysteries (associated with Demeter and Persephone) lasted nearly 2000 years and were considered the greatest spiritual institution of the ancient Mediterranean world. Many Greek philosophers including Plato, Aristotle, and Cicero were initiates.',
'The Mystery Schools understood something that modern religious education often forgets: there is a fundamental difference between information about spiritual reality and direct experience of it. Knowing that consciousness is immortal is categorically different from experiencing one''s own consciousness surviving a symbolic death. The initiatory structure was specifically designed to create the latter — and this experiential knowledge (gnosis) was considered the highest human achievement.',
'ancient Greece mystery school initiation Eleusis sacred',
ARRAY['mystery schools','eleusis','initiation','ancient greece','gnosis']),

(2,'Hermetic Wisdom',4,15,
'Paracelsus, the Renaissance alchemist and physician, revolutionised medicine by:',
'["Introducing chemistry-based treatments (minerals, metals) and the idea that specific remedies target specific diseases — the foundation of pharmaceutical medicine","Discovering that all disease originates in the astral body and must be treated through spiritual means before physical medicine can work","Proving that the four humours (blood, phlegm, yellow bile, black bile) were alchemical substances requiring transmutation","Developing the first systematic surgical techniques based on Hermetic principles of correspondence"]',
0,'historical',
'Paracelsus (1493–1541) rejected Galenic humoral medicine and introduced the concept of specific remedies for specific diseases — using minerals, metals, and chemical compounds where previously only plant-based remedies were used. He introduced laudanum (tincture of opium), mercury treatments for syphilis, and the concept of the "doctrine of signatures" (a plant''s appearance indicates its medical use). He is considered one of the founders of modern pharmacology and toxicology.',
'Paracelsus demonstrates the productive tension within alchemy: his spiritual worldview (the Hermetic universe as a living organism governed by correspondences) actually led him to practical medical innovations rather than away from them. His belief that understanding cosmic correspondences would reveal remedies was a flawed premise that nonetheless generated genuinely useful results — an example of how esoteric frameworks can produce empirical discoveries even when their foundational assumptions are questionable.',
'Paracelsus alchemy medieval medicine pharmacy Renaissance',
ARRAY['paracelsus','alchemy','medicine','renaissance','pharmacy']),

