-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
(3,'Gnosticism',1,5,
'In Gnostic cosmology, the Demiurge is best described as:',
'["A lesser, flawed creator god who fashioned the material world while mistaking himself for the supreme deity","The highest divine being — the Gnostic name for the God of Abraham","The divine feminine principle that descended into matter to animate creation","An evil cosmic force equivalent to Satan in Christian orthodoxy"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The Demiurge (Greek: craftsman) in Gnostic thought is the creator of the material world — but crucially, not the highest God. Typically portrayed as an ignorant or arrogant lesser deity who created the imperfect material realm and falsely believes himself supreme, many Gnostic systems identified the Demiurge with the God of the Old Testament. The true supreme God (the Monad or Bythos) transcends material creation entirely and is characterised by perfect love and knowledge.',
'The Gnostic Demiurge solves a profound theological problem: if there is an all-good, all-powerful supreme deity, why is the world full of suffering and limitation? The Gnostic answer: the supreme deity did not create this world. A lesser, flawed being did. This is not hopeless nihilism — the Gnostic vision affirms that the divine spark within each human is genuinely connected to the transcendent supreme being, and that liberation (return to the Pleroma) is genuinely possible.',
'Gnostic cosmology light darkness divine emanation ancient symbols',
ARRAY['gnosticism','demiurge','cosmology','creator','theodicy']),

(3,'Gnosticism',1,5,
'The Nag Hammadi Library discovered in 1945 in Egypt is historically significant because it contains:',
'["52 mostly Gnostic texts including the Gospel of Thomas — primary sources of Gnostic Christianity buried around 390 CE","The oldest known complete Hebrew Bible predating the Dead Sea Scrolls by 400 years","The lost writings of Plato including a complete version of the Timaeus","Ancient Egyptian magical papyri that prove the existence of Hermetic mystery schools"]',
0,'historical',
'The Nag Hammadi Library is a collection of 52 mostly Gnostic texts discovered in a sealed earthenware jar near Nag Hammadi, Egypt. They were likely buried around 390 CE to protect them from early Church authorities who condemned Gnosticism as heresy. The most famous text is the Gospel of Thomas — 114 sayings attributed to Jesus with no narrative context — which many scholars believe preserves very early traditions.',
'The Nag Hammadi discovery dramatically changed our understanding of early Christianity, revealing that Christian diversity in the 2nd–3rd centuries was far greater than orthodox tradition acknowledges. Gnostic Christians were not a bizarre fringe — they were sophisticated theological communities who read many of the same texts as proto-orthodox Christians but interpreted them through a radically different cosmological lens.',
'Nag Hammadi Egypt ancient scrolls Gnostic discovery library',
ARRAY['nag hammadi','gnosticism','early christianity','gospel of thomas']),

(3,'Gnosticism',4,15,
'Who is Sophia in Gnostic mythology and what is her central dramatic role?',
'["The divine feminine aeon whose desire to know the Father without her consort caused her to fall into matter, generating the Demiurge and the material world","A mortal woman who achieved gnosis and became the first human to escape the material realm and return to the Pleroma","The consort of the Demiurge who attempts to limit his power over human souls","A Gnostic name for Mary Magdalene, who preserved Jesus''s secret teachings after the Crucifixion"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Sophia (Greek: wisdom) is a divine feminine aeon dwelling in the Pleroma. In her desire to know or emanate the ineffable Father (the Monad) without her divine consort, she generates a formless, incomplete being — which becomes the Demiurge, the creator of the material world. Sophia herself partially falls into matter in grief and longing, and her rescue and restoration is central to the Gnostic cosmic drama.',
'Sophia''s myth encodes a profound psychological truth: the desire to grasp what transcends conceptual understanding generates a kind of exile from wholeness. The material world, in this telling, is not the result of divine intention but of divine yearning. The cosmos is born from wisdom''s longing to know the unknowable — framing existence not as a prison designed by an evil creator, but as the unintended consequence of love reaching beyond its proper bounds.',
'Sophia wisdom divine feminine light Byzantine sacred art',
ARRAY['sophia','wisdom','gnosticism','divine feminine','aeons']),

(3,'Gnosticism',4,15,
'The Gospel of Thomas presents the Kingdom of God as:',
'["An inner, present reality experienced through self-knowledge — not a future apocalyptic event or external place","The physical realm that Jesus will establish after his Second Coming in glory","A realm accessible only to initiates who have received the secret baptism of light","The Gnostic Pleroma, accessible only after death and the stripping away of material attachments"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The Gospel of Thomas (Saying 3): "The Kingdom is inside of you and it is outside of you." Saying 113: "His disciples said to him, When will the Kingdom come? Jesus said, It will not come by waiting for it... Rather, the Kingdom of the Father is spread out upon the earth, and men do not see it." This presents enlightenment as a present inner realisation rather than a future cosmic event.',
'The contrast between Thomas and the Synoptic Gospels is essentially the contrast between mystical immediacy and apocalyptic expectation. Thomas''s Jesus is not preparing humanity for an imminent end — he is pointing at what is already and always present. This aligns the Gospel of Thomas with the mystical traditions of the East (Zen, Advaita Vedanta) far more than with mainstream Christianity, suggesting either a genuinely different tradition about Jesus or a remarkably early synthesis of Eastern and Western mysticism.',
'Gospel Thomas ancient Coptic papyrus wisdom sayings',
ARRAY['gospel of thomas','kingdom of god','gnosis','sayings of jesus','inner kingdom']),

(3,'Gnosticism',12,50,
'What distinguishes Valentinian Gnosticism from other Gnostic schools?',
'["Its sophisticated 30-aeon Pleroma system and its use of mainstream Christian texts with allegorical Gnostic interpretation — making it the most intellectually developed Gnostic school","Its complete rejection of the Old Testament as the work of the Demiurge and insistence on a purely spiritual Jesus","Its synthesis of Platonic philosophy with Egyptian mysticism, making it the Gnostic school closest to Neoplatonism","Its democratic structure — unlike other Gnostic schools, Valentinianism had no elite of pneumatics and treated all initiates equally"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Valentinus (c. 100–160 CE) developed the most elaborate Gnostic cosmological system — a Pleroma of 30 aeons arranged in 15 pairs (syzygies) emanating from the supreme Monad — and was the most intellectually sophisticated of the Gnostic teachers. Uniquely, Valentinians read and used the canonical Gospels but interpreted them allegorically through their cosmological framework. Valentinus nearly became Bishop of Rome — Gnosticism came very close to being mainstream Christianity.',
'The near-election of Valentinus to the papacy is one of history''s great "what ifs." Had Valentinus become Bishop of Rome, Christianity''s subsequent development would have been radically different — more mystical, more philosophically sophisticated, more focused on direct inner experience, and likely far more syncretic with Neoplatonism and Eastern wisdom. The choice of the proto-orthodox framework over the Valentinian shaped Western civilisation for two millennia.',
'Valentinus Gnostic Pleroma ancient Rome Christianity',
ARRAY['valentinus','gnosticism','pleroma','aeons','early christianity']),

(3,'Gnosticism',12,50,
'The Gnostic concept of the "divine spark" (pneuma) within humans states that:',
'["Each human contains a fragment of divine light/consciousness that is foreign to the material world and is destined to return to the Pleroma","The human spirit is a creation of the Demiurge, imperfect but capable of improvement through moral effort","Divine consciousness is not present in individual humans but only in the collective of the community of believers","The spark of divinity was placed in humans by the supreme God as a gift but does not confer any special destiny or ability"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Gnostic anthropology divides humans into three types based on their composition: hylics (dominated by matter, incapable of gnosis), psychics (balanced between matter and spirit, capable of faith and moral improvement), and pneumatics (containing the divine spark, capable of gnosis and direct return to the Pleroma). The pneumatic''s divine spark is not earned or developed — it is inherent, though covered by the veils of matter and ignorance.',
'The Gnostic doctrine of the pneuma — the divine spark buried in matter, foreign to its environment, longing to return — is one of the most psychologically resonant teachings in all of religious history. It speaks directly to the experience of feeling fundamentally out of place in the material world, of sensing that there is something within that does not belong to ordinary existence. Whether understood literally or metaphorically, it has provided deep consolation to countless spiritual seekers across two millennia.',
'divine spark light consciousness Gnostic emanation cosmos',
ARRAY['divine spark','pneuma','gnosticism','human nature','pneumatics']),

(3,'Gnosticism',1,5,
'What is the Gnostic term "Pleroma"?',
'["The divine fullness — the realm of perfect divine light and the totality of divine emanations (aeons)","The material world — considered an imperfect shadow of divine reality","The process of spiritual purification through which humans return to the divine","The Gnostic equivalent of Hell — a realm of dense matter where souls are trapped between incarnations"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Pleroma (Greek: fullness, completeness) refers to the divine realm in its totality — where the supreme God (the Monad) and all the divine emanations (aeons) dwell in perfect unity. The Pleroma stands in absolute contrast to the Kenoma — the emptiness or deficiency of the material world. The Gnostic spiritual path involves recognising one''s divine spark as belonging to the Pleroma and ultimately returning to it.',
'The concept of Pleroma maps onto what mystical traditions call the Absolute or Godhead — the undifferentiated ground of being from which all manifestation emerges. The Gnostic innovation is to place this in radical contrast to the material world, creating a cosmic drama of exile and return that gives ultimate meaning to human spiritual striving. The nostalgia for the Pleroma — the homesickness of the divine spark — is Gnosticism''s most enduring emotional truth.',
'Pleroma divine light sacred emanations Gnostic cosmology',
ARRAY['pleroma','gnosticism','divine realm','aeons','fullness']),

