-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
(4,'Eastern Traditions',1,5,
'What are the Four Noble Truths at the foundation of Buddhist teaching?',
'["Suffering exists; suffering has a cause (craving); suffering can end; the Eightfold Path leads to its ending","Life is suffering; the self is real but imprisoned; karma is inescapable; only monks can be liberated","The body is impure; sensations are unsatisfactory; mind is impermanent; consciousness is empty","Non-attachment, non-violence, truthfulness, and compassion are the four foundations of liberation"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The Four Noble Truths: 1) Dukkha — suffering/dissatisfaction pervades conditioned existence; 2) Samudaya — the origin of suffering is craving (tanha) and clinging; 3) Nirodha — the cessation of craving leads to the cessation of suffering (nirvana); 4) Magga — the Eightfold Path leads to this cessation. These were the Buddha''s first teaching after his enlightenment, delivered at Sarnath.',
'What makes the Four Noble Truths radical is not the observation that life contains suffering — every religion acknowledges this. The radical move is locating the cause of suffering not in external circumstances or divine punishment, but in the mind''s own craving and clinging. This makes liberation genuinely possible through inner transformation rather than depending on external conditions — a profoundly empowering diagnosis.',
'Buddha statue meditation Sarnath India dharma teaching',
ARRAY['buddhism','four noble truths','dukkha','dharma','nirvana']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',1,5,
'The first line of the Tao Te Ching establishes its central teaching by:',
'["Immediately declaring that the Tao which can be named is not the eternal Tao — pointing beyond language to the wordless absolute","Describing the ten thousand things that emerge from the Tao''s infinite creative power","Comparing the Tao to water — the softest substance that overcomes the hardest","Beginning with wu wei — the principle of non-action through which all things are accomplished"]',
0,'philosophical',
'The Tao Te Ching opens: "The Tao that can be Tao''d is not the eternal Tao. The name that can be named is not the eternal name." This immediate paradox establishes the entire teaching: the ultimate principle of reality (the Tao) transcends all conceptualisation and language. Any attempt to define or capture it in words already distorts it — yet the text then spends 80 chapters using words to point at what transcends words.',
'The opening paradox of the Tao Te Ching is structurally identical to the Gnostic apophatic theology of the Monad, the Advaita teaching that Brahman is "neti neti" (not this, not this), and the Zen master''s refusal to define enlightenment. All genuine mystical traditions begin with the same insight: the ultimate reality is wordless, and all teachings about it are fingers pointing at the moon — not the moon itself.',
'Tao Te Ching ancient Chinese philosophy scroll Laozi',
ARRAY['taoism','tao te ching','laozi','wu wei','paradox']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',4,15,
'Advaita Vedanta''s teaching "Atman is Brahman" (tat tvam asi) means:',
'["The individual self is identical with ultimate reality — there is only one consciousness, appearing as multiplicity through the power of maya","The individual soul is separate from God but can merge with him through devotion and surrender","Individual consciousness is an illusion; only Brahman (the universal body) is ultimately real","The self must transcend itself through spiritual practice to become God as a new, higher state"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Advaita (non-dual) Vedanta, systematised by Adi Shankaracharya in the 8th century CE, teaches that the individual self (Atman) and ultimate reality (Brahman) are not merely similar or connected — they are identical. The appearance of multiplicity and separateness is maya (not illusion in the sense of non-existence, but misperceived as ultimately real). Liberation (moksha) is the direct recognition of this non-dual nature — not achieving something new but removing the misunderstanding that obscures what was always true.',
'The equation Atman = Brahman is the most radical non-dualism in the world''s philosophical traditions. It does not say God is great and humans are lesser. It says the consciousness looking out of your eyes is the same consciousness that is the universe. There are not two consciousnesses — just one. This teaching, when genuinely understood, dissolves not just religious hierarchy but the very subject-object division that structures ordinary experience.',
'Hindu temple Vedanta India sacred ancient philosophy',
ARRAY['vedanta','advaita','atman','brahman','non-duality']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',4,15,
'In yogic and tantric traditions, kundalini energy is described as:',
'["A coiled serpent energy at the base of the spine that rises through chakras toward the crown, producing spiritual awakening","The universal life force (prana) that flows through all living things and can be cultivated through breathing","A state of deep meditation where individual consciousness merges temporarily with universal consciousness","The sacred feminine aspect of God (Shakti) that must be reunited with the masculine (Shiva) through celibacy"]',
0,'esoteric',
'Kundalini (Sanskrit: coiled one) is described in tantric and yogic traditions as a dormant spiritual energy coiled at the base of the spine (muladhara chakra). Through specific practices (asana, pranayama, meditation, mantra), this energy can be awakened and guided upward through the seven chakras along the sushumna nadi (central energy channel) to the crown chakra (sahasrara), producing samadhi. Contemporary researchers like Stanislav Grof have documented powerful psychological phenomena associated with kundalini awakening.',
'The kundalini model is one of the most detailed maps of the human energy body ever developed. Whether understood literally as a bioelectric force or metaphorically as a description of psychological transformation, it has proven useful for practitioners across 2000+ years. The specificity of the chakra system — different emotional and spiritual qualities associated with each centre — allows for a form of inner diagnostics that Western psychology is only beginning to develop parallels for.',
'kundalini yoga chakra spine energy meditation India',
ARRAY['kundalini','chakras','yoga','tantra','energy','awakening']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',12,50,
'What is the fundamental difference between Advaita Vedanta and Kashmir Shaivism?',
'["Advaita sees the world as maya (superimposed illusion); Kashmir Shaivism sees the world as Shiva''s real divine play (lila)","Advaita affirms a personal God; Kashmir Shaivism denies any personal aspect of the absolute","Advaita requires renunciation; Kashmir Shaivism permits householder engagement with the world","They are essentially identical — both emerged from the same 8th-century Shankaracharya commentaries"]',
0,'philosophical',
'While both are non-dual, they differ profoundly on the status of the manifest world. Advaita Vedanta teaches that Brahman alone is real and the world of multiplicity is superimposed through maya/avidya (ignorance) — it must ultimately be seen through and transcended. Kashmir Shaivism (especially Abhinavagupta''s Trika system) teaches that the world is the real expression of Shiva''s divine consciousness — not illusion to be negated but the play (lila/vimarsha) of the Absolute recognising itself through apparent multiplicity.',
'This distinction has enormous practical implications: Advaita''s path tends toward renunciation and dissolution of engagement with the world, while Kashmir Shaivism''s path of Recognition (Pratyabhijna) allows for full engagement with life, sensation, and creativity as expressions of divine consciousness. The Shaiva view that "everything is Shiva playing hide-and-seek with himself" is perhaps the most joyful and world-affirming form of non-dualism ever developed.',
'Kashmir Shaivism Shiva temple India ancient',
ARRAY['kashmir shaivism','advaita','shiva','non-duality','recognition']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',12,50,
'The Zen koan "What is the sound of one hand clapping?" is designed to:',
'["Exhaust the conceptual mind so that direct awakening (satori) can occur in the space beyond rational thought","Test whether a student has memorised the correct answer from their teacher''s oral transmission","Teach students to think creatively and laterally outside conventional frameworks","Demonstrate that sound is a mental construction with no inherent external reality"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Zen koans are paradoxical questions or statements specifically designed to frustrate and exhaust the conceptual, discriminating mind. The mind that operates through categories, logic, and language cannot solve the koan because the koan has no conceptual solution. When the student wrestles with the koan intensely enough and the thinking mind finally collapses in exhaustion, the direct awareness that underlies all mental activity becomes apparent — this is satori (sudden awakening).',
'The koan system represents one of the most sophisticated pedagogical technologies ever developed for the specific purpose of inducing awakening. Unlike gradual path traditions that suggest enlightenment comes through accumulated practice over decades, the koan tradition suggests it can occur suddenly when the right conditions are met. Both the sharpest practitioner and the most confused student can have the same koan — the difference is not intelligence but the depth of inquiry.',
'Zen Buddhism Japan meditation koan temple monk',
ARRAY['zen','koan','satori','awakening','buddhism','mindfulness']),

(4,'Eastern Traditions',4,15,
'The Buddhist concept of "anatman" (non-self) teaches that:',
'["There is no permanent, unchanging self — what we call "I" is a constantly changing stream of experiences with no fixed essence","The self is real but must be transcended through spiritual practice to achieve liberation","Individual consciousness is an illusion created by karma — only the cosmic Brahman is truly real","The self continues after death as an unchanging soul that reincarnates until enlightenment"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Anatman (Sanskrit: no-self; Pali: anatta) is one of Buddhism''s three marks of existence. The Buddha taught that what we call the "self" is not a fixed entity but a flowing stream of five constantly changing aggregates (skandhas): form, sensation, perception, mental formations, and consciousness. There is no unchanging "soul" or essence behind these — the sense of a permanent self is a cognitive error that generates clinging and suffering.',
'The doctrine of anatman is simultaneously the most counter-intuitive and the most liberating Buddhist teaching. Counter-intuitive because our entire social and psychological structure is built around the reality of the self. Liberating because if the self is not a fixed thing but a process, then change is not just possible but inevitable — and the suffering caused by clinging to a permanent self dissolves when the self is directly seen as a process rather than a thing.',
'Buddhist meditation no self Zen temple Japan',
ARRAY['anatman','anatta','non-self','buddhism','skandhas']),

