(5,'Consciousness',1,5,
'Near-death experiences (NDEs) are remarkable for cross-cultural consistency. Which element is most universally reported?',
'["A sensation of moving toward a brilliant, overwhelmingly loving light","Meeting specific religious figures appropriate to the experiencer''s cultural background","A life review where all earthly experiences are re-experienced simultaneously","An out-of-body experience seeing one''s physical body from above"]',
0,'empirical',
'Raymond Moody documented NDEs in Life After Life (1975), identifying consistent elements: leaving the body, a dark tunnel, a brilliant light of overwhelming love, meeting deceased relatives or spiritual beings, a panoramic life review, and returning transformed — often with a profound loss of fear of death and shift in values. The tunnel-and-light experience is reported across cultures, ages, and religious backgrounds with remarkable consistency.',
'The consistency of NDE phenomenology across cultures is precisely what makes it scientifically interesting and philosophically challenging. If NDEs were simply the brain''s dying hallucinations filtered through cultural expectations, we would expect far greater cultural variation. The consistent core experience — the light described as infinitely loving and more real than ordinary reality — suggests either a genuine encounter with something beyond the physical body, or a hard-wired human neurological response to dying that itself raises profound questions.',
'light consciousness near death experience bright tunnel',
ARRAY['nde','near death','consciousness','afterlife','moody']),

(5,'Consciousness',1,5,
'The Default Mode Network (DMN) in neuroscience is active primarily during:',
'["Rest, self-referential thought, and mind-wandering — it is suppressed during focused tasks and strongly reduced by psychedelics and meditation","Processing sensory information from the external environment — it is the brain''s primary input-processing system","Social cognition and understanding other people''s minds — the neural basis of empathy","Automatic functions like breathing and heartbeat — the brain''s autopilot system"]',
0,'empirical',
'The Default Mode Network is a set of brain regions (medial prefrontal cortex, posterior cingulate cortex, angular gyrus) active during resting states and deactivated during focused external tasks. It is associated with self-referential thought, mind-wandering, imagination of the future, and the narrative construction of personal identity. Research shows psychedelics like psilocybin dramatically suppress DMN activity — correlating with ego dissolution and mystical states.',
'The DMN can be understood as the neural substrate of the ego — the brain''s mechanism for generating and maintaining the continuous narrative story of a separate self. When the DMN is suppressed (through meditation, psychedelics, or certain disease states), people report experiences ranging from flow states to mystical union. This suggests that what we call the "self" is not an eternal soul but an active construction — precisely what Buddhist and Advaita traditions have been teaching for 2000 years.',
'brain MRI neural network consciousness neuroscience',
ARRAY['neuroscience','default mode network','ego','psychedelics','consciousness']),

(5,'Consciousness',4,15,
'The "hard problem of consciousness" (David Chalmers, 1995) refers to:',
'["Why and how subjective experience (qualia) arises from physical processes — why there is something it is like to be conscious","How the brain integrates information from multiple sensory systems into unified perception","Why consciousness evolved — what selective advantage does subjective awareness provide","How humans maintain continuous personal identity despite constant neural change"]',
0,'empirical',
'Chalmers distinguished between "easy problems" of consciousness (explaining how the brain processes information, integrates data, reports internal states — mechanistic explanations) and the "hard problem": why is there subjective experience at all? Why does neural activity produce qualia — the felt quality of redness, the taste of coffee, the ache of longing? Why is there something it is like to be conscious? This question has resisted all neuroscientific explanation.',
'The hard problem reveals a fundamental gap in the materialist worldview: all objective descriptions describe structure, function, and behaviour — never the intrinsic qualities of experience. This is not a problem that more brain imaging will solve; it is a conceptual gap. Some philosophers conclude consciousness must be fundamental to reality (panpsychism); others deny qualia are real; a few suggest we need an entirely new conceptual framework — perhaps one that ancient traditions of the East were already pointing toward.',
'consciousness brain philosophy mind qualia experience',
ARRAY['hard problem','consciousness','qualia','philosophy of mind','chalmers']),

(5,'Consciousness',4,15,
'Researcher Rick Strassman found that DMT (dimethyltryptamine) is endogenous — meaning it is produced within the human body. Where has it been confirmed to exist?',
'["In blood, cerebrospinal fluid, and the lungs — the pineal gland production hypothesis is popular but unconfirmed in humans","Exclusively in the pineal gland, where it regulates the sleep-wake cycle alongside melatonin","Only in the liver and adrenal glands, produced during extreme psychological stress","In the retina only, where it functions to filter visual information during dream states"]',
0,'empirical',
'Rick Strassman''s research (DMT: The Spirit Molecule) administered DMT to subjects under controlled conditions and found consistent reports of encounters with intelligent entities, geometric visions, and experiences of alternate dimensions. Endogenous DMT has been confirmed in blood, urine, cerebrospinal fluid, and the lungs. The popular pineal gland hypothesis has not been confirmed by direct measurement in living humans, though it remains scientifically viable.',
'The endogenous presence of DMT — the same molecule responsible for some of the most profound altered states known — raises a fascinating question. If the brain already produces this substance, might there be naturally occurring states (deep meditation, hypnagogia, near-death experiences, dream states) where its production is elevated? The fact that one of the most powerful psychedelic molecules is also a normal component of human biochemistry suggests that the capacity for mystical experience may be hardwired into human biology.',
'DMT molecule brain research psychedelic pineal gland consciousness',
ARRAY['dmt','endogenous','psychedelics','consciousness','strassman']),

(5,'Consciousness',12,50,
'Giulio Tononi''s Integrated Information Theory (IIT) proposes consciousness corresponds to Φ (phi). Its most controversial implication is:',
'["Any system with high integrated information has some degree of consciousness — including simple circuits — while some AI systems might have near-zero consciousness despite computational power","Consciousness is purely computational — sufficient processing power automatically generates subjective experience","The thalamus is the sole seat of consciousness — the cortex processes information without any experiential quality","Consciousness is a quantum phenomenon exclusive to biological microtubules in neurons"]',
0,'empirical',
'IIT proposes that consciousness = integrated information (Φ) — a measure of how much a system''s whole generates more information than the sum of its parts. Crucially, this implies any system with high Φ has some degree of consciousness — potentially including simple electronic circuits. It also implies that current AI feedforward networks might have near-zero consciousness despite apparent intelligence, while certain simple biological systems might have genuine experience.',
'IIT''s most radical implication is a form of structural panpsychism — consciousness is not exclusive to biological brains but is a property of certain organisational structures wherever they occur. This would mean the universe contains far more consciousness than we ordinarily assume — not because rocks think, but because any system with sufficient integrated information has some quality of experience. This resonates with the Hermetic teaching that the All is Mind — that consciousness is a fundamental feature of reality.',
'brain consciousness information neuroscience mind IIT',
ARRAY['IIT','integrated information','Tononi','consciousness','phi','panpsychism']),

(5,'Consciousness',12,50,
'Stanislav Grof''s holotropic breathwork is based on his research with LSD in the 1960s, which suggested:',
'["Human consciousness contains transpersonal dimensions — including what appear to be memories of biological birth, ancestral experience, and collective archetypes — accessible through non-ordinary states","LSD produces hallucinations that are random neural noise with no psychological significance","The unconscious mind contains only personal repressed material (contra Jung) — there is no collective dimension","Psychedelics are purely physiological — their psychological effects are entirely explained by serotonin receptor binding"]',
0,'empirical',
'Grof conducted over 4000 LSD sessions with patients and observed experiences that transcended personal biography — including authentic re-experiences of birth trauma with physiological correlates, apparent memories of ancestral events, and what appeared to be experiences of cosmic consciousness, death and rebirth, and mythological/archetypical content that matched cross-cultural traditions the subjects had no prior knowledge of. He developed a comprehensive cartography of the psyche based on these observations.',
'Grof''s research suggests that human consciousness is vastly larger than ordinary waking awareness — that it contains within it a history extending beyond personal biography to biological birth, evolutionary heritage, and even cosmic dimensions. Whether these transpersonal experiences represent genuine access to realities beyond the individual psyche (as Grof concluded) or very deep projections of universal cognitive structures, they consistently produce the most therapeutically powerful and meaning-generating experiences known to modern psychology.',
'holotropic breathwork consciousness therapy transpersonal',
ARRAY['grof','holotropic','LSD','transpersonal','consciousness','birth']),

(5,'Consciousness',1,5,
'What distinguishes "lucid dreaming" from ordinary dreaming?',
'["The dreamer is aware they are dreaming while remaining in the dream state — allowing deliberate choice and navigation","The dream content is unusually vivid and emotionally intense — more real-seeming than ordinary dreams","The dreamer can receive accurate information about the external world while sleeping","The dream has symbolic meaning that directly relates to the dreamer''s waking psychological situation"]',
0,'empirical',
'Lucid dreaming occurs when the dreamer becomes aware they are dreaming while remaining in the dream state. First scientifically confirmed by Keith Hearne (1975) and Stephen LaBerge (1980) using pre-agreed eye movement signals from within the dream state, lucid dreaming has been extensively studied. Techniques include MILD (mnemonic induction of lucid dreams), WILD (wake-induced lucid dreaming), and reality testing. Advanced lucid dreamers report being able to navigate and control the dream environment deliberately.',
'Lucid dreaming provides a unique philosophical laboratory: a state in which consciousness is fully active and self-aware while the physical body is inert and sensory input is entirely internally generated. The lucid dreamer''s ability to observe the construction of an entire experiential world — complete with consistent physics, other characters, and spatial depth — while knowing it is a mental construction offers a direct experiential demonstration of consciousness''s creative power.',
'lucid dreaming consciousness sleep REM dream state',
ARRAY['lucid dreaming','consciousness','sleep','REM','laberge']),

-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
-- REALM 6: PSYCHOLOGY
-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
(6,'Psychology',1,5,
'Carl Jung proposed that beneath the personal unconscious lies:',
'["The collective unconscious — a layer shared by all humans containing universal archetypes and inherited psychological patterns","The superconscious — a higher dimension accessible only through deep meditation and spiritual practice","The racial unconscious — memories specific to ethnic groups preserved across generations through epigenetics","The cosmic unconscious — a unified field of human thought connecting all minds through a quantum field"]',
0,'empirical',
'Jung proposed that beneath the personal unconscious (containing forgotten memories, repressed content, subliminal impressions) lies the collective unconscious — a deeper layer shared by all humans and even across species. Unlike the personal unconscious (acquired in one lifetime), the collective unconscious is inherited and contains archetypes: universal, primordial patterns of psychic energy that structure human experience across all cultures — the hero, shadow, anima/animus, wise old man, great mother.',
'Jung''s concept of the collective unconscious bridges psychology and anthropology, explaining why the same themes appear in myths across cultures with no historical contact. Whether understood literally (as a shared psychic field) or metaphorically (as a description of deep human commonalities), the collective unconscious has proven enormously generative — for psychotherapy, for understanding mythology, and for making sense of the universal themes in spiritual experience across all traditions.',
'Jung psychology unconscious archetypes mandala',
ARRAY['jung','collective unconscious','archetypes','psychology','psyche']),

(6,'Psychology',1,5,
'In Jungian psychology, the "Shadow" refers to:',
'["The collection of repressed, denied, and rejected aspects of the personality that operate unconsciously","The mask or persona we show to the world to meet social expectations","The unconscious contrasexual element in men (anima) and women (animus)","The autonomous complexes formed around traumatic childhood experiences"]',
0,'empirical',
'The Shadow contains everything the conscious ego refuses to identify with — qualities considered unacceptable, weak, or immoral, as well as genuine positive qualities rejected by the childhood environment (the "golden shadow"). The Shadow is not simply evil — it is the repository of unlived life. When not integrated, the Shadow is projected outward onto others — scapegoating, prejudice, and tribal hatred are collective Shadow projections.',
'The Shadow''s most important characteristic is that it does not disappear when ignored — it grows in power. Every quality we refuse to acknowledge in ourselves gets projected onto others and becomes visible as an intense reaction (fascination, disgust, admiration, or hatred) toward those qualities in other people. The person you most intensely dislike often carries qualities belonging to your own Shadow. This insight makes shadow work both personally liberating and essential for understanding social conflict.',
'shadow psychology darkness integration unconscious Jung',
ARRAY['jung','shadow','psychology','shadow work','projection']),

(6,'Psychology',4,15,
'Jung defined "individuation" as:',
'["The lifelong process of integrating all parts of the psyche into a conscious, differentiated whole centred on the Self (not the ego)","The developmental stages through which a child becomes a socialised member of their cultural group","The process by which repressed trauma memories are recovered and integrated into conscious awareness","The differentiation of psychological types (introvert/extrovert) that determines personality"]',
0,'empirical',
'Individuation is Jung''s term for the central process of psychological development — the emergence of the individual Self from original undifferentiated wholeness. It involves integrating the persona (social mask), confronting and integrating the Shadow, engaging with the anima/animus (contrasexual inner figures), and ultimately centring identity on the Self (the totality of the psyche, both conscious and unconscious) rather than the ego alone. Individuation is a lifelong journey — never complete.',
'Individuation is essentially what all genuine spiritual traditions describe as awakening or liberation, translated into psychological language. The difference is that Jungian individuation does not require transcendence of the ego or union with a metaphysical absolute — it requires a reorientation of the ego''s relationship to the whole psyche. The goal is not to become egoless but to become ego-conscious: aware that the ego is a part of a larger wholeness, not its centre.',
'individuation psychology Jung mandala wholeness growth',
ARRAY['jung','individuation','self','psychology','wholeness']),

(6,'Psychology',4,15,
'Jung coined "synchronicity" to describe:',
'["Meaningful coincidences — acausal connections between inner psychic events and outer physical events that share meaning but not physical causation","A phenomenon where highly charged emotional states cause people to fall into identical thinking patterns simultaneously","The unconscious tendency of therapy patients to pattern their behaviour on the therapist''s expectations","Dreams that accurately predict future external events"]',
0,'empirical',
'Jung defined synchronicity as an "acausal connecting principle" — meaningful coincidence between an inner (psychic) event and an outer (physical) event sharing meaning but connected by no physical cause-and-effect. The classic example: a patient describes a dream about a golden scarab beetle when an actual scarab-like insect taps on Jung''s window. Jung saw synchronicity as evidence that psyche and matter are not entirely separate domains, participating in a common underlying order (the unus mundus).',
'Synchronicity remains one of the most philosophically rich and empirically problematic of Jung''s contributions. Physicists Wolfgang Pauli and David Bohm engaged with the concept seriously, wondering if it points to a deeper order beneath the apparent separation of mind and matter. If mind and matter share a common underlying order, then meaningful coincidences are not violations of causality but windows into a more fundamental connectedness — what the Hermeticists called the unus mundus.',
'synchronicity coincidence meaningful universe signs',
ARRAY['jung','synchronicity','meaningful coincidence','pauli','unus mundus']),

(6,'Psychology',12,50,
'Joseph Campbell''s monomyth identifies what three main stages of the hero''s journey?',
'["Departure (from the ordinary world), Initiation (trials and transformation), Return (bringing wisdom back to the community)","Childhood (innocence), Crisis (the wound), Transcendence (achieved spirituality)","Ego (ordinary consciousness), Shadow (encounter with darkness), Self (achievement of wholeness)","Innocence, Experience, and Higher Innocence — William Blake''s three stages of spiritual evolution"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Campbell identified the monomyth structure in The Hero with a Thousand Faces (1949), arguing that myths across all cultures follow the same fundamental pattern. The hero receives a call to adventure, crosses a threshold into an extraordinary world, faces tests and allies, reaches the innermost cave where the central ordeal occurs, seizes the reward, and makes the road back — transformed and ready to bring wisdom to the ordinary world.',
'The monomyth is not just a literary pattern — it is a map of psychological transformation. Every stage corresponds to a psychological challenge: the call is the emergence of the unconscious into consciousness; the initiation is the confrontation with the Shadow and death of the old self; the return is the integration of what has been learned. Understanding this structure explains why the same story — whether Star Wars, the Odyssey, or a shamanic initiation — produces the same recognition across all cultures.',
'hero journey myth adventure quest transformation voyage',
ARRAY['campbell','monomyth','hero journey','mythology','archetypes']),

(6,'Psychology',12,50,
'Viktor Frankl''s logotherapy, developed during his time in Nazi concentration camps, proposes that:',
'["The primary human motivation is not pleasure (Freud) or power (Adler) but the search for meaning — and meaning can be found even in unavoidable suffering","The human psyche contains a transpersonal ''spiritual unconscious'' separate from the personal unconscious that connects to absolute values","Psychological healing requires confronting the existential void directly rather than filling it with distractions or substitutes","Suffering is always a symptom of repressed unconscious content — eliminating the repression eliminates the suffering"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Viktor Frankl (1905–1997) developed logotherapy (logos = meaning) based on his observation that in the concentration camps, those most likely to survive were not the physically strongest but those who had a reason to live — a purpose, someone to return to, a work to complete. He proposed that the primary human motivation is the will to meaning (contra Freud''s will to pleasure and Adler''s will to power), and that meaning can be found even in unavoidable suffering through the attitude one takes toward it.',
'Frankl''s insight — that we cannot always choose our circumstances but can always choose our response to them — converges remarkably with both Stoic philosophy and Viktor Frankl''s contemporary, Martin Heidegger. The idea that meaning is found rather than created, and that it provides the psychological resources to endure anything, has proven one of the most clinically effective ideas in all of psychotherapy — particularly for patients facing terminal illness, severe trauma, or irreversible loss.',
'Viktor Frankl logotherapy meaning concentration camp philosophy',
ARRAY['frankl','logotherapy','meaning','holocaust','existential psychology']),

(6,'Psychology',1,5,
'The Jungian concept of "persona" refers to:',
'["The social mask or public face we present to the world — necessary for social functioning but dangerous when identified with","The authentic self that emerges through the individuation process","The shadow side of the personality that contains repressed qualities","The inner image of the ideal partner projected onto actual romantic partners"]',
0,'empirical',
'The persona (Latin: mask, the masks worn by Roman actors to indicate their role) is the social face presented to the world — the professional identity, the cultural role, the image crafted to meet social expectations. The persona is not inherently false or bad — we need different faces for different contexts. The danger, which Jung called "persona identification," occurs when a person mistakes the mask for themselves — when the doctor forgets they are not only a doctor, or the father forgets he is not only a father.',
'The persona system is one of Jung''s most immediately recognisable concepts because we can all observe it directly in ourselves — the different faces we wear at work, with family, with strangers, with intimates. The spiritual danger of persona identification is the same as what the Gnostics called hylics who cannot perceive the divine spark within them: so thoroughly do they identify with the social role that the deeper selfhood — which the persona exists to protect and mediate — is forgotten entirely.',
'mask persona psychology role social identity',
ARRAY['jung','persona','mask','psychology','social identity']),

-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
-- REALM 7: QUANTUM PHYSICS
-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
(7,'Quantum Physics',1,5,
'The double-slit experiment demonstrates that electrons and photons:',
'["Behave as waves (producing interference patterns) when not observed, but as particles when measured — the act of measurement collapses the wave function","Always behave as particles — wave behaviour is a statistical artifact of large numbers of particles","Produce interference patterns only when fired at high velocity; slow particles behave as pure particles","Switch between wave and particle depending on temperature — cold particles behave as waves"]',
0,'empirical',
'Individual electrons fired one at a time at a barrier with two slits create an interference pattern on the detector screen — as if each electron passes through both slits simultaneously and interferes with itself. However, when a detector is placed to observe which slit the electron passes through, the interference pattern disappears and electrons behave as particles. This is the measurement problem — one of the most profound and unresolved puzzles in physics.',
'The double-slit experiment puts in stark experimental form the deepest mystery of quantum mechanics: the role of observation in determining physical reality. Before measurement, the electron exists in a superposition of all possible states — simultaneously going through both slits. The act of measurement (interaction with a macroscopic detector) collapses this superposition into a definite state. Whether this collapse is physical, informational, or involves consciousness remains deeply contested.',
'quantum physics laboratory double slit wave particle experiment',
ARRAY['quantum physics','double slit','wave particle duality','measurement']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',1,5,
'Quantum entanglement — what Einstein called "spooky action at a distance" — describes:',
'["When two particles are correlated such that measuring one instantly affects the other''s state regardless of the distance between them","When particles become physically linked and must be physically separated to end their connection","A quantum force field exchanged between particles at the speed of light when separated","The tendency of identical particles to cluster together creating molecular bonds"]',
0,'empirical',
'When two particles become entangled (typically by interacting and then separating), they share a quantum state. Measuring one particle and collapsing its quantum state instantly correlates with the other particle''s state, regardless of distance. Bell''s theorem (confirmed by Alain Aspect in 1982) demonstrated that no local hidden variable theory can explain these correlations — the universe is genuinely non-local at the quantum level.',
'Quantum entanglement''s non-locality suggests that at the most fundamental level, the universe does not consist of separate objects that interact through forces. Entangled particles remain a single system regardless of spatial separation. David Bohm''s interpretation suggests this points to an underlying "implicate order" in which everything is enfolded into everything else — a holographic universe where separation is a feature of the surface (explicate) order rather than a fundamental fact.',
'quantum entanglement particles physics laboratory non-local',
ARRAY['quantum entanglement','non-locality','Bell theorem','quantum physics']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',4,15,
'David Bohm''s "implicate order" proposes that:',
'["The visible physical world (explicate order) is a projection from a deeper enfolded dimension (implicate order) where all things are holographically interconnected","Quantum mechanics is incomplete and hidden variables determine the apparent randomness of quantum events","The universe operates like a neural network where particles communicate through quantum fields","Reality consists of parallel orders — the physical and mental — that operate independently but occasionally interact"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Physicist David Bohm proposed that the universe has two levels: the explicate order (the visible world of separate objects and events) and the implicate order (a deeper dimension where everything is enfolded into everything else, like patterns in a hologram). The explicate order is a continuous projection from the implicate. Entanglement and non-locality are explainable because apparently separated particles are still connected at the implicate level.',
'Bohm''s implicate order is one of the few scientific frameworks that directly parallels ancient mystical cosmologies: an underlying Unity from which apparent multiplicity emerges and to which it remains connected. It resonates with Indra''s net in Buddhism (each jewel reflects all others), the Hermetic principle of correspondence, and the Gnostic Pleroma. Bohm collaborated with Krishnamurti for decades, exploring where physics and consciousness research overlap.',
'holographic universe physics implicate order cosmos Bohm',
ARRAY['bohm','implicate order','holographic universe','quantum physics','explicate']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',4,15,
'The holographic principle in theoretical physics proposes that:',
'["All information describing a volume of space is encoded on its two-dimensional boundary — the universe may be fundamentally a hologram","Reality is composed of light frequencies that our brains decode into a three-dimensional experience","Consciousness creates holographic reality through the observer effect in quantum mechanics","The universe repeats itself at every scale — galaxies mirror atoms in structure"]',
0,'empirical',
'The holographic principle, arising from black hole physics (Bekenstein-Hawking), proposes that the maximum information encodable in a region of space is proportional to its surface area (not its volume). This suggests our apparently 3-dimensional universe could be the holographic projection of information encoded on a 2-dimensional boundary. The principle is a theorem in string theory (AdS/CFT correspondence) and has significant implications for understanding space, information, and reality.',
'Michael Talbot''s The Holographic Universe (1991) popularised the idea that the holographic principle might explain both quantum physics and anomalous consciousness phenomena. Neuroscientist Karl Pribram had already proposed the brain works holographically. If both brain and universe operate on holographic principles, consciousness and physical reality may share a deeper structural kinship — the "as above, so below" of Hermetic thought may have a scientific substrate.',
'holographic universe space information physics theory',
ARRAY['holographic principle','information physics','universe','quantum gravity']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',12,50,
'John Wheeler''s "delayed choice" experiment suggests that:',
'["An observer''s decision (whether to measure which path a photon took) can apparently affect the photon''s behaviour retroactively — the past is not fixed until observed","The future determines the present through backward causation","Consciousness can choose which quantum branch of reality to experience","Observation affects quantum systems only at the moment of observation, not before or after"]',
0,'empirical',
'Wheeler''s delayed-choice experiment (confirmed 2007) demonstrates that the decision to observe which slit a photon passes through can be made after the photon has already passed through the slits — yet the photon retroactively adjusts its behaviour to match the observation. If the measurement is made, no interference pattern forms; if not, the interference pattern is present. This suggests the photon''s "choice" of wave or particle is contingent on the future observation.',
'Wheeler concluded that the universe is "participatory" — observers are not passive spectators but active participants in bringing reality into being. "No phenomenon is a phenomenon until it is an observed phenomenon." This implies that the past is not fully defined until information about it becomes irreversible. The implication that reality is fundamentally open and co-created connects quantum physics to participatory mystical traditions — the view that consciousness and universe are co-arising.',
'quantum physics experiment laboratory photon light measurement',
ARRAY['wheeler','delayed choice','quantum physics','observer','participatory universe']),

(7,'Quantum Physics',12,50,
'What is the "measurement problem" in quantum mechanics?',
'["Quantum systems exist in superposition (multiple states simultaneously) until measured — but physics cannot explain what constitutes a measurement or why measurement collapses the superposition","Quantum measurements always introduce uncertainty due to the observer disturbing the system — Heisenberg''s uncertainty principle","The equations of quantum mechanics cannot make precise predictions — only probabilistic ones — which constitutes an incomplete description of reality","Quantum systems cannot be measured at absolute zero temperature because measurement itself introduces thermal energy"]',
0,'empirical',
'The measurement problem: quantum mechanics mathematically describes particles existing in superpositions of multiple states simultaneously (the wave function). When measured, the wave function "collapses" to a single definite state. But the theory itself provides no physical mechanism for this collapse — why does observation produce a definite outcome? Proposed solutions include Copenhagen (collapse is real but unexplained), Many Worlds (all outcomes occur in branching parallel universes), and QBism (quantum states are subjective degrees of belief).',
'The measurement problem is not merely a technical puzzle — it is a profound philosophical crisis for the materialist worldview. Materialism assumes a physical world that exists independently of observation. Quantum mechanics suggests, at minimum, that the mathematical description of physical systems depends fundamentally on observation. Whether this implicates consciousness in the constitution of reality (as idealist interpretations suggest) or merely reflects the limits of our descriptive tools remains the deepest open question in the philosophy of physics.',
'quantum measurement superposition physics wave function collapse',
ARRAY['measurement problem','superposition','wave function','quantum physics','many worlds']),

