-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
(9,'Comparative Religion',1,5,
'In Sufism, "fana" refers to:',
'["The annihilation or dissolution of the ego-self in union with God — the mystical death of the personal self","The 40-day solitary retreat practiced by advanced Sufi seekers","The sacred poetry tradition using music and dance to access divine union","The Sufi concept of the heart as the true spiritual centre of the human being"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Fana (Arabic: annihilation, passing away) is the Sufi term for the mystical state in which the individual ego dissolves in union with the Divine. The personal self — with its desires, attachments, and sense of separate existence — ceases to function as the centre of experience. What remains is baqa (subsistence in God) — the individual continues to function in the world, but from the perspective of unity rather than separation. Rumi and Al-Hallaj most famously described this state.',
'Al-Hallaj was executed in 922 CE for declaring "I am the Truth" — interpreted as blasphemy (claiming to be God) rather than as a mystical statement about the dissolution of self in divine unity. The theological controversy around fana reveals a fundamental tension in theistic mysticism: how does the mystic''s experience of unity with God relate to orthodox doctrine of God''s absolute transcendence? Sufism''s answer: both are true simultaneously — the mystic and God are one, and the mystic and God are also infinitely different.',
'Sufi whirling dervish mysticism Islamic meditation prayer',
ARRAY['sufism','fana','mysticism','islam','rumi','al-hallaj']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',1,5,
'The Kabbalistic Tree of Life (Etz Chaim) consists of ten sefirot representing:',
'["The ten attributes or emanations through which the Infinite (Ein Sof) reveals itself and creates all reality","The ten stages of purification through which the soul passes after death","The ten commandments given to Moses encoded in divine symbolic form","Ten angelic hierarchies arranged in a ladder between earth and the divine throne"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Tree of Life is Kabbalah''s central symbolic map — ten sefirot (counting/sphere) arranged in a specific pattern connected by 22 paths. The sefirot represent ten attributes or dimensions through which the unknowable Ein Sof (Infinite) progressively reveals and limits itself to create the universe. From Keter (Crown — pure divine will) through Chokhmah (Wisdom), Binah (Understanding), and the remaining seven, the Tree maps the divine creative process.',
'The Tree of Life is one of the most comprehensive symbolic systems ever developed — applied to cosmology, psychology, ethics, mystical experience, biblical interpretation, and ritual magic. Its 22 paths correspond to the 22 letters of the Hebrew alphabet and the 22 Major Arcana of the Tarot. The convergence of Kabbalah, Hebrew letters, and Tarot in Renaissance esotericism created one of the most richly layered symbolic languages in Western mystical tradition.',
'Kabbalah Tree of Life Jewish mysticism sefirot sacred ancient',
ARRAY['kabbalah','tree of life','sefirot','jewish mysticism','ein sof']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',4,15,
'The "perennial philosophy" (philosophia perennis), described by Aldous Huxley, proposes that:',
'["All the world''s mystical traditions share a common core of metaphysical truth about the nature of consciousness and ultimate reality","Religious traditions are culturally determined projections of universal psychological needs rather than responses to external transcendent reality","Eastern religions are philosophically superior to Western ones due to their focus on inner experience over external doctrine","Religion and science share the same underlying epistemology — both are empirical investigations of different aspects of reality"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Huxley''s 1945 book documented a common metaphysical framework across Hindu Vedanta, Buddhist Mahayana, Christian mysticism (Eckhart), Islamic Sufism, Taoism, and indigenous traditions. The core: reality is ultimately a divine Ground (infinite consciousness, Brahman, Tao, Ground of Being); humans have the capacity to identify with this Ground; recognising this identity is the highest human purpose; the path involves ego-transcendence, ethical purification, and contemplative practice.',
'The perennial philosophy is simultaneously its own tradition and a meta-framework for understanding all traditions. Critics note it may minimise genuine differences between traditions in pursuit of a unifying narrative. Defenders argue it correctly identifies the experiential core beneath doctrinal differences. The fundamental question it poses: is the remarkable convergence of mystical experience across all cultures evidence that mystics are contacting the same genuine reality? Or is it convergent cognitive responses to similar contemplative practices?',
'world religions unity mysticism philosophy light enlightenment',
ARRAY['perennial philosophy','huxley','mysticism','comparative religion','unity']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',4,15,
'Meister Eckhart, 14th-century Dominican mystic, was condemned by the Pope for teaching:',
'["The identity of the soul with God in the Godhead — that the ground of the soul and the Ground of God are identical","That Jesus was not historically real — that the Christ is solely an inner spiritual reality","That salvation could be achieved without the Church through direct mystical experience alone","That matter is divine — a form of pantheism denying God''s transcendence"]',
0,'historical',
'Eckhart''s condemned propositions centred on his teaching about the Grunt (ground or foundation) — the deepest level of both God and the soul. He taught that in the Grunt, God and the soul are identical. "The eye through which I see God is the same eye through which God sees me." This was condemned as heretical (Papal bull In Agro Dominico, 1329), though some Catholic thinkers today consider the condemnation historically contingent rather than doctrinally necessary.',
'Eckhart''s thought stands as perhaps the most radical expression of Christian mysticism ever formulated in orthodox theological language. His statement "the eye through which I see God is the same eye through which God sees me" is structurally identical to the Advaita teaching Tat tvam asi (That thou art). The Catholic Church condemning its own most profound mystic for teaching what Hindu Vedanta and Buddhist Prajnaparamita teach openly reveals the profound tension between mystical experience and institutional religion.',
'medieval Christian mysticism cathedral Europe gothic church',
ARRAY['Meister Eckhart','Christian mysticism','ground of soul','medieval','heresy']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',12,50,
'The Islamic concept of "tawhid" and the Sufi concept of "wahdat al-wujud" differ in that:',
'["Tawhid affirms God''s absolute oneness (monotheism); wahdat al-wujud (Ibn Arabi''s Unity of Being) goes further, declaring that all existence is a manifestation of God — a mystical monism","Tawhid is an exoteric doctrine for ordinary believers; wahdat al-wujud is the esoteric core known only to initiates","Tawhid applies to God''s transcendence (far); wahdat al-wujud applies to God''s immanence (near) — both are orthodox Islam","They are identical — wahdat al-wujud is simply the philosophical formulation of the Quranic declaration ''There is no God but God''"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Tawhid (Arabic: divine unity) is the central doctrine of Islamic theology — the absolute oneness of God, distinguished from all creation. Ibn Arabi (1165–1240 CE) developed wahdat al-wujud (Unity of Being) — the radical mystical position that there is only one Being, and all apparently distinct entities are manifestations of that one Being. While tawhid maintains a distinction between Creator and creation, wahdat al-wujud collapses this distinction — making it controversial in orthodox Islamic theology.',
'Ibn Arabi''s wahdat al-wujud represents perhaps the most sophisticated philosophical system produced by any Islamic thinker — a vast, internally consistent ontology in which God is both the Absolute Hidden (unknown in Himself) and the manifest world (known through the self-disclosure of His names and attributes). The system maps almost perfectly onto Advaita Vedanta while emerging entirely from within the Islamic Quranic tradition — demonstrating that the same mystical insight can be reached through radically different doctrinal starting points.',
'Islamic mysticism Sufi mosque ancient arabesque spiritual',
ARRAY['tawhid','wahdat al wujud','ibn arabi','sufism','unity of being']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',12,50,
'Zoroastrianism''s theological innovation, which directly influenced Judaism, Christianity, and Islam, was:',
'["Ethical dualism — the cosmos is a battlefield between Ahura Mazda (Wise Lord/Good) and Angra Mainyu (Destructive Spirit/Evil) — individual humans must choose sides","Absolute monotheism — before Zoroaster, all Middle Eastern religions were polytheistic","The concept of divine judgment after death — Egyptian mythology is the only other ancient source for this idea","The idea that a divine saviour (Saoshyant) would come at the end of time to resurrect the dead and restore paradise"]',
0,'historical',
'Zoroastrianism (founded by Zarathustra/Zoroaster, approximately 1500–1000 BCE) was the first religion to systematically develop ethical monotheism and cosmic dualism — a good God (Ahura Mazda) opposed by an evil spirit (Angra Mainyu), with humans as free agents whose moral choices affect the cosmic battle. Through the Babylonian exile (597–539 BCE), these concepts — the devil, apocalypse, resurrection, final judgment, heaven and hell as moral destinations — entered Jewish theology and subsequently Christianity and Islam.',
'The influence of Zoroastrianism on Western religion is one of the most underappreciated stories in religious history. The concepts that feel most essential to Christianity — Satan as a cosmic adversary, the resurrection of the dead, a final judgment, a messianic saviour, an apocalyptic end of history — all have their clearest pre-Christian articulation in Zoroastrian texts. When the Three Wise Men (Magi) followed the star to Bethlehem, they were likely Zoroastrian priests — the tradition that announced Christ had its roots in the oldest dualistic religion in the world.',
'Zoroaster ancient Persia fire temple Ahura Mazda',
ARRAY['zoroastrianism','ahura mazda','dualism','ancient persia','jewish influence']),

(9,'Comparative Religion',1,5,
'The Jewish concept of "Tikkun Olam" (repair of the world) in Kabbalistic tradition refers to:',
'["The cosmic process of gathering scattered divine sparks (nitzotzot) that fell into matter during the Shevirat HaKelim — the breaking of the divine vessels — and restoring them to their source","A social justice mandate requiring Jews to work for human rights and equality in the external world","The daily prayer practice that''s believed to maintain the cosmic order and prevent the universe from collapsing","The process of healing the divine feminine (Shekhinah) from her exile by performing the 613 commandments (mitzvot)"]',
0,'esoteric',
'In Lurianic Kabbalah (developed by Isaac Luria in 16th-century Safed), tikkun olam (repair/restoration) has a specific cosmic meaning: during the primordial creation, the divine light was too intense for the vessels (sefirot) that were meant to contain it, causing the Shevirat HaKelim (Breaking of the Vessels). Divine sparks (nitzotzot) fell into the material world, trapped in shells (kelipot). Every human act done with sacred intention helps gather these sparks and restore them to their divine source — each person participates in the cosmic repair.',
'Luria''s myth of the Breaking of the Vessels and the scattered sparks is one of the most psychologically resonant cosmic narratives ever developed. It answers the question of why the world contains suffering and evil not with a story of human sin but with a cosmic accident — and it places the responsibility for repair not on God but on each human being. Every mundane act, when performed with consciousness and intention, participates in the healing of the cosmos. This is the Kabbalistic version of the Gnostic return of divine sparks to the Pleroma.',
'Kabbalah Jewish mysticism divine sparks repair world cosmic',
ARRAY['tikkun olam','kabbalah','lurianic kabbalah','divine sparks','cosmic repair']),

-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
-- REALM 10: HIDDEN HISTORY
-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
(10,'Hidden History',1,5,
'In which dialogues of Plato does the story of Atlantis appear, and who describes it?',
'["Timaeus and Critias — told by Critias who claims it came from Solon via Egyptian priests","The Republic and the Phaedrus — described by Socrates as an ancient memory of his soul","The Symposium and the Phaedo — recounted by Diotima as a historical precedent for philosophical ascent","The Laws and the Statesman — told by the Athenian Stranger as a warning about hubris"]',
0,'historical',
'Plato introduced the Atlantis narrative in Timaeus and Critias (c. 360 BCE). The story is attributed to Critias, who claims to have learned it from his grandfather Critias the Elder, who heard it from Solon, who was told by Egyptian priests at Sais. The priests reportedly told Solon that the Athenians had defeated Atlantis 9000 years before Solon''s time (c. 9600 BCE), after which Atlantis was destroyed by earthquakes and floods in a single day and night.',
'The transmission chain in Plato''s account (Egyptian priests → Solon → Critias the Elder → Critias the Younger → Plato) has been cited as both evidence of the story''s historical basis and as grounds for skepticism. Egyptian priests were custodians of records spanning millennia — they told Solon that the Greeks were "children" compared to Egypt''s historical memory. Whether Plato created Atlantis as a philosophical allegory, preserved a genuine historical memory, or some combination, remains one of scholarship''s most enduring debates.',
'Plato ancient Greece scroll philosophy Atlantis ocean map',
ARRAY['atlantis','plato','timaeus','critias','ancient history']),

(10,'Hidden History',1,5,
'The Younger Dryas Impact Hypothesis (YDIH) proposes that approximately 12,800 years ago:',
'["A cosmic impact event (fragmenting comet or asteroid) triggered a rapid climate cooling that may have ended an earlier advanced civilisation","A supervolcano eruption at Yellowstone caused a millennium-long winter wiping out megafauna","Melting of the Laurentide Ice Sheet caused a catastrophic flood depositing the Younger Dryas sediment layer","A pole shift displaced Earth''s rotational axis, causing the sudden extinction of mammoths and other megafauna"]',
0,'speculative',
'The YDIH (proposed by Firestone et al., 2007) suggests a fragmenting cosmic object impacted or airburst over North America approximately 12,800 years ago, triggering the Younger Dryas cold period (sudden temperature drop lasting ~1300 years). Evidence cited includes: a platinum-rich "black mat" layer in archaeological sites across multiple continents, nano-diamonds (formed by cosmic impacts), spherules, and the extinction of North American megafauna. Some evidence is confirmed; other aspects remain contested.',
'The YDIH is significant for esoteric history because it provides a potentially scientific mechanism for a real global catastrophe at approximately the time Plato placed Atlantis''s destruction (9000 years before Solon ≈ 9600 BCE — close to 12,800 BCE). If a catastrophic impact event ended an earlier advanced civilisation and was encoded in human collective memory as flood myths (which appear in virtually every culture on Earth), the mythological record becomes potential historical testimony.',
'comet impact ancient catastrophe ice age meteorite Earth',
ARRAY['younger dryas','impact hypothesis','ancient catastrophe','comet','firestone']),

(10,'Hidden History',4,15,
'Graham Hancock''s central thesis argues that:',
'["An advanced civilisation was destroyed approximately 12,000 years ago, and its survivors seeded subsequent civilisations with astronomy, architecture, and spiritual knowledge","Ancient megaliths like the pyramids were built by extraterrestrial beings whose technology was lost when they departed","Ancient peoples were connected by a worldwide ocean-going civilisation that shared knowledge from a fixed golden age","The ancient world was unified under a single global empire whose capital was in Antarctica"]',
0,'speculative',
'Hancock argues (in Fingerprints of the Gods, Magicians of the Gods, America Before) that geological and archaeological evidence points to a lost civilisation of high sophistication that existed during the last Ice Age and was destroyed by a cosmic catastrophe approximately 12,800 years ago. Survivors transmitted astronomical, architectural, and spiritual knowledge to the emerging post-catastrophe cultures of Egypt, Sumer, and Mesoamerica — explaining why these civilisations displayed surprisingly advanced knowledge in their earliest stages.',
'Hancock''s work sits at the interesting boundary between alternative archaeology and mainstream science. His core challenge — that civilisation may be older and more developed than currently acknowledged — has gained some mainstream traction, particularly as evidence for the YDIH has accumulated and as sites like Göbekli Tepe have demonstrated complex culture far earlier than previously accepted. The mainstream archaeological establishment remains skeptical of his specific claims but cannot deny the anomalies he identifies.',
'ancient ruins archaeology stone pyramid mystery civilisation jungle',
ARRAY['graham hancock','lost civilisation','ancient history','fingerprints of gods']),

(10,'Hidden History',4,15,
'The megalithic stones at Baalbek in Lebanon are considered anomalous because:',
'["They include quarried limestone blocks weighing 800–1000 metric tons — far exceeding the capabilities of any confirmed ancient engineering technology","They contain inscriptions in a pre-Phoenician script that has never been deciphered","They were quarried and then abandoned mid-project, suggesting the builders lost their technology suddenly","Their precise dimensions encode advanced astronomical knowledge to 5 significant figures"]',
0,'empirical',
'The Baalbek platform (the Stone of the Pregnant Woman and nearby stones) includes limestone blocks weighing 800–1000 metric tons — the heaviest known quarried stones in the world. The heaviest stones in the Great Pyramid weigh approximately 80 metric tons; the Baalbek blocks are 8-12 times heavier. No crane technology in the ancient or modern world can lift a 1000-ton stone without purpose-built equipment. How stones of this size were quarried, transported, and placed with precision remains genuinely unexplained.',
'Baalbek represents one of the most concrete anomalies in ancient engineering. This is not mythology or interpretation — it is a physical fact in Lebanon. The Romans, despite their advanced engineering, did not quarry stones of this size — suggesting these blocks are from a pre-Roman construction. What civilisation quarried these stones, when, and why remains genuinely unknown to mainstream archaeology. The site forces a fundamental question: what capabilities did ancient peoples have that we have not yet properly acknowledged?',
'Baalbek Lebanon ancient stone temple Roman ruins massive block',
ARRAY['baalbek','ancient engineering','mystery','lebanon','megaliths']),

(10,'Hidden History',12,50,
'The ancient Vedic text Mahabharata describes flying vehicles called "vimanas" and weapons called "brahmastra" that many researchers compare to:',
'["Nuclear weapons and aircraft — descriptions of enormous explosions that turn sand to glass and symptoms matching radiation sickness","Metaphorical descriptions of spiritual powers (siddhis) developed through intense yogic practice","Allegorical representations of weather phenomena — vimanas as clouds, brahmastra as lightning","Actual mechanical devices powered by mercury vortex engines, confirmed by recent archaeological excavations in India"]',
0,'speculative',
'The Mahabharata and Ramayana contain detailed descriptions of vimanas (flying machines or divine vehicles) and weapons of mass destruction. The brahmastra is described as: "a single projectile charged with all the power of the Universe... it was an unknown weapon, an iron thunderbolt, a gigantic messenger of death which reduced to ashes the entire Jarasandha race." At Mohenjo-daro, archaeologists found evidence of what appears to be an ancient explosion with vitrified sand (turned to glass by extreme heat) similar to nuclear test sites.',
'The descriptions of brahmastra and the archaeological evidence at Mohenjo-daro remain genuinely contested — mainstream archaeology attributes the vitrified layer to pottery kilns or a different cause, while alternative researchers point to the descriptions'' remarkable specificity. Whether ancient India possessed or imagined advanced weapons, or whether these texts encode real historical memories of a forgotten technology, the question touches on the fundamental assumption that technological sophistication can only move in one direction: from primitive to advanced.',
'ancient India Vedic temple vimana Sanskrit manuscript',
ARRAY['vimana','brahmastra','mahabharata','ancient india','vedic civilisation']),

(10,'Hidden History',12,50,
'Robert Schoch''s geological analysis of the Great Sphinx at Giza controversially proposed that:',
'["The Sphinx''s weathering pattern indicates water erosion from heavy rainfall — suggesting construction before 7000 BCE, far earlier than the Egyptian Old Kingdom","The Sphinx was built by the Atlantean civilisation as a marker pointing to the Hall of Records beneath its paws","The Sphinx was originally a natural rock formation carved by the Nile into a lion shape and later adapted by Old Kingdom Egyptians","The Sphinx''s body shows evidence of ancient repairs using materials not available in Egypt — suggesting it was transported from elsewhere"]',
0,'speculative',
'Geologist Robert Schoch (Boston University) presented his analysis at the 1991 Geological Society of America conference, arguing that the deep, horizontal erosion patterns on the Sphinx''s body and enclosure are consistent with water weathering from heavy rainfall — not wind and sand erosion. The Sahara region had significant rainfall before approximately 5000–7000 BCE. This would place the Sphinx''s original construction thousands of years before the conventional date of c. 2500 BCE during the reign of Khafre.',
'Schoch''s geological analysis is methodologically mainstream — he applied standard geological weathering analysis to the Sphinx''s limestone. What is controversial is the implication: a monument of this sophistication in 7000+ BCE or earlier challenges the conventional timeline of human civilisation. If the Sphinx is older than currently believed, what civilisation built it? The geological evidence does not itself answer this question — it only establishes a date incompatible with the conventional attribution.',
'Great Sphinx Giza Egypt ancient erosion geology mystery',
ARRAY['sphinx','schoch','water erosion','ancient egypt','giza','old kingdom']),

(10,'Hidden History',1,5,
'The Book of Enoch, excluded from the biblical canon, describes:',
'["The Watchers — fallen angels who descended to Earth, mated with human women producing giant offspring (Nephilim), and taught humanity forbidden knowledge","The creation of the world in seven days as told from the perspective of the angels who witnessed it","The complete history of all biblical patriarchs before and after the Flood in expanded narrative form","The cosmological architecture of heaven — the seven heavens, their angelic inhabitants, and the divine throne room"]',
0,'historical',
'The Book of Enoch (1st Enoch), preserved complete only in Ethiopian Christianity but quoted in the New Testament (Jude 1:14-15), describes the Watchers — a class of angels who descended to Mount Hermon, took human women as wives, and produced giant offspring (the Nephilim, mentioned in Genesis 6:1-4). The Watchers also taught humanity various arts and sciences — metalworking, cosmetics, herb lore, astrology, and the making of weapons — considered forbidden knowledge.',
'The Book of Enoch was widely read in the Second Temple period and directly influenced the New Testament, yet was excluded from the biblical canon. The Watcher tradition — divine beings who interfered with humanity, sharing forbidden technology, and producing hybrid offspring — appears across ancient Near Eastern mythology. The Sumerian gods (Anunnaki) who descended from heaven and interacted with humans, the Greek Titans who warred with the Olympians, and the Nephilim of Genesis all share structural similarities that suggest a common ancient narrative about supernatural interference in human development.',
'ancient scroll Book of Enoch Watchers Nephilim angels',
ARRAY['book of enoch','watchers','nephilim','fallen angels','ancient texts']),

-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
-- REALM 11: SYMBOLISM
-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
(11,'Symbolism',1,5,
'In the Tarot''s Major Arcana, The Fool (card 0) represents:',
'["Pure, unlimited potential at the beginning of the Hero''s journey — the soul before it takes on the limitations of experience","Stupidity, recklessness, and the folly of spiritual seekers who pursue esoteric knowledge","A specific historical figure — the court jester who spoke truth to power in medieval courts","The final state of enlightenment — the return to divine innocence after completing the spiritual path"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Fool, typically depicted as a young figure about to step off a cliff with a pack on a staff and a white rose in hand, represents the soul at the beginning of its journey — pure potential, divine innocence, and unlimited possibility. The dog at his heels represents the voice of worldly wisdom trying to hold him back. The cliff represents the leap of faith required to begin any genuine journey. The Fool "knows nothing" — but this is the knowing of emptiness, not ignorance.',
'The Fool''s position as card 0 (before numbered existence begins) and sometimes card XXII (after the World completes the cycle) reveals its double significance: it is both beginning and end, alpha and omega of the soul''s journey. The Fool who ends the journey is not the same as the Fool who began it — the second Fool has been through all 21 cards and returned to the infinite freedom of 0, but now consciously. This is the Zen "beginner''s mind" in its deepest form.',
'Tarot Fool card spiritual journey mystical symbolic art',
ARRAY['tarot','major arcana','the fool','symbolism','archetypes']),

(11,'Symbolism',1,5,
'The Flower of Life is a geometric figure that:',
'["Contains 19 overlapping circles in a hexagonal pattern from which Metatron''s Cube and all five Platonic solids can be derived","Consists of a spiral of Fibonacci circles expanding outward from a central point","Contains 64 tetrahedra arranged in a cube — the building block of the unified field","Encodes the complete astrological chart geometrically — all 12 zodiacal positions"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Flower of Life consists of 19 complete circles (and parts of 18 more at the edges) in a hexagonal pattern. Within it, sacred geometers identify the Seed of Life (7 circles), the Egg of Life, and the Fruit of Life (13 circles). From the Fruit of Life, connecting the centres with lines produces Metatron''s Cube — a figure containing all five Platonic solids (the geometric building blocks of physical matter according to Plato). The figure appears in ancient Egypt, Assyria, Buddhist temples across Asia, and medieval Europe.',
'The worldwide appearance of the Flower of Life across cultures with no known historical contact is one of sacred geometry''s most compelling mysteries. Its mathematical properties are genuinely remarkable — it encodes the Golden Ratio, the Platonic solids, and fundamental wave interference patterns. Whether ancient peoples discovered these properties independently, shared them through lost cultural contact, or accessed them through direct geometric perception remains one of the great questions of ancient knowledge.',
'Flower of Life sacred geometry ancient pattern hexagonal circle',
ARRAY['flower of life','sacred geometry','metatrons cube','ancient symbol','platonic solids']),

(11,'Symbolism',4,15,
'The Ouroboros — the serpent eating its own tail — appears across cultures and universally symbolises:',
'["Eternal cyclical return, self-referential infinity, and the unity of all opposites — the self-contained wholeness of the universe","Death and rebirth — the serpent must die (losing its tail) before it can be reborn (regrowing the tail)","The primal chaos from which the universe emerged — the formless before the first act of creation","Time as a linear progression that curves back on itself — the universe''s ultimate fate of cyclical collapse and re-creation"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Ouroboros (Greek: tail-devourer) represents self-referential wholeness — a system that contains and generates itself. It appears in the Egyptian Book of the Dead, in Gnostic texts, in Viking mythology as Jörmungandr, in alchemical manuscripts, and in Hindu iconography. Jung interpreted it as a symbol of the collective unconscious and the beginning of individuation. Remarkably, chemist August Kekulé reported dreaming of an Ouroboros in 1865 — which revealed to him the ring structure of benzene.',
'The Ouroboros encodes a deep mathematical truth: self-reference and self-containment are fundamental features of both consciousness and certain mathematical systems. Gödel''s incompleteness theorem demonstrated that any sufficiently complex formal system contains statements that refer to the system itself — a logical Ouroboros. The universe as a closed causal loop is an Ouroboros at the cosmological scale. Ancient symbol, modern mathematics, and cosmology converge in the same figure.',
'Ouroboros serpent infinity ancient Egypt alchemy symbol',
ARRAY['ouroboros','alchemy','symbol','infinity','serpent','self-reference']),

(11,'Symbolism',4,15,
'In the Tarot, The Tower (card XVI) most accurately represents:',
'["The sudden, violent collapse of false structures and ego-based certainties — painful but ultimately liberating","The destructive power of human ambition — the Tower of Babel as a warning against overreaching","Military defeat, the destruction of kingdoms, and the end of political power","The dark night of the soul — the extended period of spiritual desolation before dawn"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Tower, typically depicting a tall tower struck by lightning with figures falling from its heights, represents the sudden, catastrophic collapse of structures that were built on false foundations — whether beliefs, relationships, identities, or worldly achievements. The lightning bolt is divine force — not malevolent but illuminating, exposing the false. What the Tower destroys was already structurally unsound; the destruction, however painful, is a precondition for building something true.',
'The Tower is perhaps the most feared card in a Tarot reading, yet it carries a deeply liberating truth: the things we cling to most desperately are often the very things that imprison us. The Tower doesn''t destroy truth — it destroys the illusion of permanence and security that we build around temporary structures. After every Tower moment — every sudden breakdown, every shattering of a certainty — there is the opportunity to build something more honest, more resilient, and more aligned with reality.',
'Tower tarot lightning symbolic art spiritual crisis transformation',
ARRAY['tarot','the tower','major arcana','symbolic art','transformation','crisis']),

(11,'Symbolism',12,50,
'In alchemy, the four stages of the Great Work (Magnum Opus) and their colours are:',
'["Nigredo (black/death) → Albedo (white/purification) → Citrinitas (yellow/dawn) → Rubedo (red/completion)","Prima Materia (red) → Solutio (blue) → Coagulatio (white) → Calcinatio (gold)","Mortificatio (black) → Separatio (white) → Coniunctio (red) → Multiplicatio (gold)","Calcination (red) → Dissolution (blue) → Separation (white) → Conjunction (black)"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The Great Work''s stages describe both literal laboratory alchemy and psychological-spiritual transformation. Nigredo: dissolution and death — confronting the shadow, the dark night of the soul. Albedo: purification — the silver Moon stage, emergence of the anima/animus in Jungian terms. Citrinitas: the transitional yellowing, first light of dawn (sometimes omitted in later alchemy). Rubedo: reddening — final transmutation into gold, the philosopher''s stone, individuation completed.',
'Jung devoted years to alchemical texts precisely because he found in the alchemists'' symbolic language the most precise pre-scientific description of the individuation process he had ever encountered. When lead becomes gold in alchemy, the ego becomes Self; when the impure metal is purified, the shadow is integrated. Ancient chemistry and modern depth psychology are secretly the same pursuit — the alchemists were doing genuine inner work while believing they were transforming metals.',
'alchemy laboratory medieval gold transformation stages mystical',
ARRAY['alchemy','great work','nigredo','rubedo','transformation','four stages']),

(11,'Symbolism',12,50,
'The number 7 appears with remarkable frequency across unrelated ancient traditions. Which of the following connections is factually accurate?',
'["Seven chakras, Seven Hermetic Principles, Seven days of creation, Seven classical planets, Seven musical notes (solfège), Seven colours of visible light — suggesting an underlying structural principle","Seven was chosen arbitrarily by different cultures as their sacred number and the similarity is coincidental","Seven represents the number of wounds of Christ and all other sevens derive from Christian influence on world culture","The number seven appears in nature (seven continents, seven seas, seven types of organism) leading cultures to adopt it symbolically"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The frequency of the number 7 across independent ancient traditions is genuinely remarkable: 7 chakras in the Hindu/yogic system, 7 Hermetic Principles (Kybalion), 7 classical planets known to the ancient world (Moon, Mercury, Venus, Sun, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn), 7 days of the week named after these planets, 7 notes of the diatonic musical scale, 7 colours of visible light (ROY G BIV), 7 days of the Genesis creation, 7 sacraments in Catholicism, 7 seals in Revelation.',
'The ubiquity of 7 suggests it may reflect something fundamental about how reality organises itself rather than being an arbitrary cultural choice. The 7 classical planets ordered the ancient cosmos; the 7 notes of the musical scale divide the octave in the most natural way; the 7 chakras map to major nerve plexuses of the human body. Whether this is coincidence, universal archetypical resonance, or evidence of a common ancient source of knowledge transmitted across cultures remains one of sacred geometry''s most enduring questions.',
'sacred number seven mystical symbols cosmic pattern',
ARRAY['sacred numbers','seven','numerology','symbolism','patterns']),

(11,'Symbolism',1,5,
'The Tarot''s Major Arcana card "The World" (card XXI) represents:',
'["Completion, wholeness, and the successful integration of all experiences — the soul''s triumphant return to the beginning transformed","Death — the end of the physical world and the soul''s judgment before the divine throne","The material world as illusion — a reminder to release attachment to earthly things","Cosmic consciousness — the mystic''s final dissolution of self into the infinite"]',
0,'esoteric',
'The World (or The Universe) depicts a dancing figure at the centre of a laurel wreath, often surrounded by the four fixed signs of the zodiac (lion, bull, eagle, angel) — the same four beings that appear in Ezekiel''s vision and in Revelation. The dancing figure represents the soul that has successfully integrated all aspects of the psyche represented by the previous 20 cards — having descended into the underworld (The Moon), faced death (Death card), transformed through the alchemical fire (The Tower), and achieved wholeness.',
'The World card stands as the ultimate promise of the Tarot system: that the long journey through all the experiences of life — including its darkest and most challenging cards (The Tower, Death, The Devil, The Moon) — leads not to destruction but to completion. The dancer at the centre is the individuated Self of Jungian psychology, the Atman recognised as Brahman, the pneuma returned to the Pleroma. Every major Arcana card encountered was a necessary station on this journey.',
'Tarot World card completion wholeness mystical spiritual art',
ARRAY['tarot','the world','major arcana','completion','wholeness']),

-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
-- REALM 12: ETHICS & WISDOM
-- ════════════════════════════════════════════
(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',1,5,
'"The unexamined life is not worth living" — in what context did Socrates make this statement?',
'["At his trial in 399 BCE, defending his philosophical practice even as he faced the death penalty","In a dialogue with Meno about whether virtue can be taught","When speaking to young Athenians who wished to join his philosophical circle","In his final conversation with friends on the day of his execution"]',
0,'historical',
'Socrates made this declaration at his trial in 399 BCE, as recorded in Plato''s Apology. Facing charges of impiety and corrupting the youth of Athens, Socrates refused to abandon philosophical practice even to save his life. When offered the possibility of exile or philosophical silence, he declined — the practice of examining himself and others was identical with living as a human being. He was convicted and chose death by hemlock over exile or silence.',
'Socrates'' choice of death over the abandonment of philosophy has shaped Western ethical thought for 2400 years. For Socrates, philosophy was not an academic discipline but a way of being — a practice of honest self-examination and genuine conversation that constituted the most fully human life possible. The statement was made not in a classroom but in a courtroom, by a man who had written nothing, facing execution — the ultimate test of whether the examined life was genuinely worth living.',
'Socrates ancient Athens philosophy trial hemlock Greece',
ARRAY['socrates','apology','philosophy','examined life','ethics','death']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',1,5,
'The Stoic "dichotomy of control" (Epictetus) teaches that:',
'["Freedom comes from focusing exclusively on what is up to us (thoughts, intentions, responses) and accepting everything else with equanimity","We should control all aspects of our environment to achieve the conditions for virtue","Both external circumstances and internal states can be controlled through sufficient willpower","The wise person achieves emotional control by suppressing feelings through rational effort"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Epictetus opens the Enchiridion with the fundamental Stoic distinction: some things are "up to us" (eph''hēmin) — our judgments, impulses, desires, and aversions — and some things are "not up to us" — body, reputation, property, political office. Suffering arises from treating things not up to us as if they were. Freedom and equanimity arise from aligning desire and aversion exclusively with what is genuinely within our control: the quality of our own character, judgment, and response.',
'The Stoic dichotomy of control is simultaneously ancient wisdom and a practical psychological tool of extraordinary power. Modern cognitive-behavioural therapy (CBT) is built on essentially the same insight: much psychological suffering arises from attempting to control what cannot be controlled while ignoring what can be cultivated. Epictetus — a former slave — developed this teaching under literal conditions of external powerlessness, making his insight both autobiographically demonstrated and universally applicable.',
'Stoic philosophy Marcus Aurelius Rome ancient wisdom scroll',
ARRAY['stoicism','epictetus','control','freedom','ethics','dichotomy']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',4,15,
'Plato''s Allegory of the Cave: after escaping to see the Sun (the Form of the Good), the philosopher''s obligation is to:',
'["Return to the cave and attempt to liberate the prisoners — even at the risk of death — because justice requires sharing true knowledge","Stay outside in the sunlight and contemplate the Forms — the cave requires no revisiting once the Good is perceived","Create a new city of philosophers outside the cave where escaped prisoners can live in truth","Record the nature of the Sun and the Forms in writing that cave-dwellers can eventually read"]',
0,'philosophical',
'In the Republic, Plato describes the philosopher who escapes the cave as having an obligation to return. Having seen the Form of the Good, the philosopher is more qualified than anyone to govern justly — but will appear foolish to those still watching shadows. The returning philosopher risks ridicule and potentially death (a clear allusion to Socrates). Yet justice — for Plato — requires this sacrifice: those who have seen the Good must serve those who have not.',
'The Cave''s politics are as radical as its metaphysics: Plato argues that the philosopher has an obligation to return to the imperfect world of politics not because it is pleasant but because justice demands it. The philosopher who refuses to govern will be governed by worse people. This is Plato''s answer to the Socratic question: given that the examined life is the best life, what is that life''s responsibility to those who have not examined theirs? The answer: everything. The truth obligates.',
'Plato allegory cave philosophy shadows light Greece',
ARRAY['plato','allegory cave','forms','philosopher king','justice']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',4,15,
'Viktor Frankl''s logotherapy proposes that the primary human motivation is:',
'["The search for meaning — and meaning can be found even in unavoidable suffering through the attitude one takes toward it","The will to pleasure — and suffering is always a sign of blocked or frustrated pleasure-seeking","The will to power — and suffering results from not having sufficient mastery over one''s environment","The avoidance of death anxiety — and all human activity is ultimately motivated by terror management"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Frankl (1905–1997) developed logotherapy based on his observation that in Nazi concentration camps, those most likely to survive were not the physically strongest but those who had a reason to live — a purpose, someone to return to, a work to complete. He proposed that the primary human motivation is the will to meaning (contra Freud''s will to pleasure and Adler''s will to power), and that meaning can be found even in unavoidable suffering through the attitude one takes toward it.',
'Frankl''s insight — that we cannot always choose our circumstances but can always choose our response to them — converges with both Stoic philosophy and with Buddhist teachings on acceptance of dukkha. "He who has a why to live can bear almost any how" (Nietzsche, quoted by Frankl). The idea that meaning provides the psychological resources to endure anything has proven one of the most clinically effective ideas in all of psychotherapy — particularly for patients facing terminal illness or irreversible loss.',
'Viktor Frankl meaning suffering philosophy psychology',
ARRAY['frankl','logotherapy','meaning','will to meaning','suffering']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',12,50,
'Aristotle''s "eudaimonia" — often translated as happiness — more precisely means:',
'["Flourishing — living in accordance with one''s highest faculties (reason and virtue) over a complete life — an activity, not a feeling","Pleasurable sensory experience — the accumulation of positive feelings over a lifetime","Contentment and freedom from disturbance — the Aristotelian equivalent of Epicurean ataraxia","Success in achieving goals and earning community respect through accomplished deeds"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Eudaimonia (eu = good + daimon = spirit) is Aristotle''s term for the highest human good — the goal that everything else aims at. It is activity of the soul in accordance with its highest virtue (arete), sustained over a complete life. Crucially, eudaimonia is not a feeling but an activity — a way of living and functioning. A person living according to reason and virtue, exercising capacities fully, engaged in meaningful relationships and civic life, is eudaimon regardless of momentary emotional state.',
'The distinction between eudaimonia and hedonia (pleasure/positive affect) describes two radically different visions of the good life. Hedonia is about how good one feels; eudaimonia is about how well one is functioning as a human being. Research in positive psychology (Seligman''s PERMA model) has rediscovered this distinction empirically: the factors predicting long-term wellbeing (meaning, engagement, positive relationships, accomplishment) do not always produce pleasurable feelings in the moment. Aristotle was right that the best life is not necessarily the most pleasant one.',
'Aristotle ancient philosophy Greece ethics virtue flourishing',
ARRAY['aristotle','eudaimonia','flourishing','virtue','ethics','happiness']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',12,50,
'The Taoist concept of "wu wei" (non-action) teaches:',
'["Acting in alignment with the natural flow of reality rather than forcing — effortless action that achieves without struggle","Complete passivity and inaction — the sage does nothing because all action creates karma","The renunciation of all goals and desires — achievement is impossible without surrendering the desire to achieve","Acting only through the body, not through the mind — all mental interference with natural impulse is wu wei''s opposite"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Wu wei (Chinese: non-action, non-doing) is one of the most misunderstood concepts in Taoism. It does not mean inaction or laziness — it means action that is so naturally aligned with the Tao (the underlying pattern of reality) that it requires no force, produces no resistance, and leaves no trace. The metaphors used for wu wei — water carving the Grand Canyon, a skilled craftsman whose tool moves as if by itself, the tree that bends in the storm and survives while the rigid tree breaks — all point to effortless effectiveness.',
'Wu wei''s paradox is that the most effective action is often the action that feels like non-action — so perfectly aligned with conditions that it seems effortless. This maps onto the psychological experience of "flow" (Csikszentmihalyi) in which peak performance occurs precisely when the effortful self steps aside. It also resonates with the Zen concept of mushin (no-mind) in martial arts — maximum effectiveness through minimum interference. The Taoist sage and the master athlete are engaged in the same fundamental discipline.',
'Tao Te Ching Taoist philosophy water flow nature wisdom',
ARRAY['taoism','wu wei','non-action','effortless','flow','tao']),

(12,'Ethics & Wisdom',1,5,
'The Buddhist concept of "karuna" (compassion) is defined as:',
'["The wish for all beings to be free from suffering — combined with the motivation to actively relieve that suffering","Feeling pity or sympathy for those less fortunate than oneself — a passive emotional response","The recognition that all beings share the same fundamental nature — a philosophical rather than emotional insight","Unconditional love for all beings regardless of their actions — equivalent to the Christian concept of agape"]',
0,'philosophical',
'Karuna (Sanskrit/Pali: compassion) is specifically defined in Buddhism as the wish for all beings to be free from suffering — combined with the motivation to actively relieve that suffering. It is distinguished from pity (which looks down at others'' suffering from a distance) and from grief (which is overwhelmed by suffering). Karuna is the active, engaged movement toward suffering in order to relieve it. Together with metta (loving-kindness), mudita (sympathetic joy), and upekkha (equanimity), it forms the four brahmaviharas — the divine abodes.',
'The Buddhist distinction between compassion and pity is psychologically precise and clinically important. Compassion (feeling with) maintains one''s own stability while engaging with another''s pain. Pity (feeling sorry for) creates a hierarchy between the compassionate person and the suffering person. Empathy (feeling as) can lead to compassion fatigue when poorly regulated. The Buddhist brahmaviharas training system is essentially a sophisticated programme for developing the psychological capacities needed to engage with suffering without being overwhelmed by it.',
'Buddhist meditation compassion lotus flowers peaceful temple',
ARRAY['buddhism','karuna','compassion','brahmavihara','loving kindness']);

